SW)<ref name=\"nswft-iar\">{{cite web |title=NSW Fair Trading: Incorporated Associations Register |url=http://associationspr.fairtrading.nsw.gov.au/Default.aspx |access-date=15 February 2016}}</ref> and ABN-30077002923<ref name=\"abr-abn\">{{cite web |title=ABR: Historical details for ABN 30 077 002 923 |url=http://abr.business.gov.au/SearchByAbnHistory.aspx?abn=30077002923 |access-date=15 February 2016|date=November 2014 }}</ref>\n|formerly = Australian Vaccination Network (AVN) 1994-2014,<ref name=\"abc-sceptical\" />  Australian Vaccination-Skeptics Network 2014-2018{{R|\"The Skeptic Zone 510\"}}\n|website = [http://avn.org.au/ AVN.org.au]\n|key_people = Tasha David, Brett Smith,<ref name=\"brett-smith-scd\">{{cite news |title=Anti-vaccine groups say they are pro-choice |work=[[Sunshine Coast Daily]] Qld. |date=10 September 2015 |author=APN Newsdesk |url=http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/anti-vaccine-group-denies-opposing-all-vaccines/2770698/ |accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref> Greg Beattie, Meryl Dorey, Judy Wilyman.}}\n{{Alternative medicine sidebar|conspiracy}}\n\nThe '''Australian Vaccination-risks Network Inc.''', formerly known as the '''Australian Vaccination-Skeptics Network''', and before that known as the '''Australian Vaccination Network''' ('''AVN'''), is an Australian [[anti-vaccination]] pressure group<ref name=HCCCfinal/> registered in [[New South Wales]]. As Australia's most controversial anti-vaccination organisation,<ref name=aspvaxbi/> it has [[lobbying|lobbied]] against a variety of vaccination-related programs, downplayed the danger of childhood diseases such as [[measles]] and [[pertussis]], championed the cause of alleged vaccination victims, and promoted the use of ineffective alternatives such as [[homeopathy]]<ref name=\"perthnow01\">{{cite news |url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/news/muddying-the-water-on-vaccination/story-fn6mhct1-1226406819206 |title=Muddying the water on vaccination |author=Hansen, Jane |date=24 June 2012 |work=[[Perth Now]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620223325/https://www.docdroid.net/fy0oDZV/archiveis-pukdw.docx.html |archivedate=20 June 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[chiropractic]].\n\nThe vast majority of [[Physician|doctors]] agree that opposition to vaccination applies to a [[Fringe science|fringe medical science]] viewpoint.<ref name=\"guardianrd\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/16/anti-vaccination-activists-should-not-be-given-a-say-in-the-media |title=Anti-vaccination activists should not be given a say in the media |author=Dunlop, Rachael |authorlink=Rachael Dunlop|date=16 October 2013 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> The group has been described as a provider of \"misleading, inaccurate, and deceptive\" vaccination information by the New South Wales [[Health Care Complaints Commission]] (HCCC),<ref name=HCCCfinal/> and has been heavily criticised by doctors and other experts on immunisation.<ref name=HCCClateline/> The group has been called the \"stronghold of the anti-vaccination movement\" in Australia and is subject to widespread criticism from medical professionals, scientists and other proponents of vaccination.<ref name=\"smith\">{{cite news |title=Dick Smith criticises anti-vaccination 'misinformation' |work=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |date=7 August 2009 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/08/07/2649266.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507033715/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/08/07/2649266.htm |archivedate=7 May 2010 |author=.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stop the Bogus Australian Vaccination Network |work=Australian Images |url=http://www.australianimages.com.au/opinion/vaccination.php |date=20 November 2009 |accessdate=12 September 2009 |author=. }}</ref><ref name=\"wooldridge\">{{Cite press release |title=Anti-Immunisation lobby misleading the media |work=Australian Federal Government, Dept of Health and Ageing |date=15 October 1998 |author=Wooldridge, Michael |url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/health-archive-mediarel-1998-mw21298.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308011313/http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/health-archive-mediarel-1998-mw21298.htm |archivedate=8 March 2010}}</ref> It has also been criticised for harassing the parents of a victim of vaccine-preventable disease,<ref name=\"abc-harass\">{{cite web |last1=Cannane|first1=Steve |title=Anti-vaccination group accused of harassing parents |url=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2010/s2951651.htm  |accessdate=2 February 2015 |work=[[Lateline]] |date=12 July 2010 |publisher=ABC TV |quote=[HCCC report] ... noted accusations that the AVN harassed the parents of a child who died of whooping cough last year, after they'd advocated the importance of childhood vaccination}}</ref> and for promoting the false idea that [[shaken baby syndrome]] is actually vaccine injury.<ref name=\"sciblog-vilest\">{{cite web |author=Gorski, David |title=The vilest antivaccine lie that won't die: Shaken baby syndrome as \"vaccine injury\" |url=http://scienceblogs.com/insolence/2012/02/07/the-vilest-antivaccine-lie-that-wont-die/ |work=ScienceBlogs |accessdate=2 February 2015 |date=7 February 2012 |quote=... one of the most disturbing antivaccine claims of all is the assertion that shaken baby syndrome is a \"misdiagnosis for vaccine injury.}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 October 2010, the organisation's right to raise funds was stripped from it by the [[New South Wales Office of Liquor, Gaming and Racing]], stating that its appeals had \"not been conducted in good faith for charitable purposes\".<ref name=\"olgr-abc\"/> In December 2012, the New South Wales Office of Fair Trading issued an order for the group to change its name within two months or be de-registered. The department described the group's name as being \"misleading and a detriment to the community\".<ref name=\"antivax2_ref\"/><ref name=\"northernstarchangename\">{{cite news |title=Anti-vaccine group must change 'misleading' name |work=[[Northern Star (Australian newspaper)|The Northern Star]] |date=17 December 2012 |author=. |url=http://www.northernstar.com.au/news/anti-vaccine-group-must-change-misleading-name/1685224/ |accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"adelaidenowchangename\">{{cite news |title=Anti-vaccine set forced to fess up |author=Penberthy, David |date=20 December 2012 |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/opinion/david-penberthy-anti-vaccine-set-forced-to-fess-up/story-e6freall-1226541363953 |accessdate=21 December 2012 |work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|AdelaideNow]]}}</ref> The group changed its name in February 2014.<ref name=\"abc-sceptical\">{{cite news |last=Foschia |first=Liz |title=Australian Vaccination Network changes name to reflect sceptical stance |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-03-11/nsw-anti-vaccination-group-changes-its-name-after-complaints/5312910 |date=11 March 2014 |accessdate=11 March 2014 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |quote=The Australian Vaccination Network has changed its name to one that more clearly reflects its anti-vaccination views.}}</ref> In July 2018 the group changed its name to Australian Vaccination-risks Network Inc. citing that many in their group ''\"did not feel comfortable with having the word 'skeptics' in\"'' their name as the reason for the change. The group decided that the word \"skeptic\" too closely aligned them with [[Skeptical movement|Scientific Skepticism]] organisations such as the [[Australian Skeptics]].<ref name=\"The Skeptic Zone 510\">{{cite web |last=Saunders |first=Richard |authorlink=Richard Saunders (skeptic) |title=The Skeptic Zone #510 - 29.July.2018 |url=http://skepticzone.libsyn.com/the-skeptic-zone-509-22july2018-0 |website=The Skeptic Zone |publisher=The Skeptic Zone |accessdate=21 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121230034/http://skepticzone.libsyn.com/the-skeptic-zone-509-22july2018-0 |archivedate=21 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=David |first1=Tasha |title=We have changed our name! |url=https://avn.org.au/2018/07/we-have-changed-our-name/ |publisher=Australian Vaccination-risks Network Inc. |accessdate=22 November 2018 |date=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Organisation==\n\nThe Australian Vaccination-Skeptics Network was formed in 1994 as the Vaccination Awareness Network by Meryl Dorey,<ref name=\"occam\">{{Cite book |title=OCCAM's Nightmare |last=Davis |first=S. Peter |publisher=Lulu Enterprises Inc |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-304-03018-4 |location=U.S.A. |pages=172\u2013177}}</ref> a medically unqualified<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/rendezview/babies-are-dying-because-of-narcissistic-activists-it-must-stop/news-story/fd6ae864fe1a4aac11cdd435cf55a56f|title=Babies are dying because of narcissistic activists. It must stop|last=Hansen|first=Jane|date=2 April 2017|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]]|access-date=2 April 2017}}</ref> American who moved to Australia with her Australian husband, saying she got involved after her eldest son was allegedly adversely affected by [[DPT vaccine|DPT]] and [[MMR vaccine]]s administered when he was a child.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Howden|first1=Saffron|title=Mother's crusade began the night her baby stopped breathing|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/mothers-crusade-began-the-night-her-baby-stopped-breathing-20100727-10uf8.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=28 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=Crikey2016>{{Cite news |url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2016/03/01/the-relentless-terrifying-rise-of-the-anti-vax-movement/ |title=The relentless, terrifying rise of the anti-vax movement |author=McDonald, Zara |date=1 March 2016 |work=[[Crikey]] |accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> \nThe group applied for tax-deductible charity status through the [[Australian Taxation Office]] and finally obtained it in 2002; it lost that status in 2007 by allowing it to lapse, and obtained it again in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Benson|first1=Kate|title=Vaccine opponent risks charity status|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/vaccine-opponent-risks-charity-status-20100804-11fog.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=5 August 2010}}</ref>  In 2010 the group's tax-exempt status was revoked by the NSW Office of Liquor, Gaming and Racing after an audit of the organisation finding that AVN fundraising appeals had not been conducted in good faith for charitable purposes, had been improperly administered and were not in the public interest.<ref name=\"olgr-gazette\">{{Cite news |title=Instrument of Revocation |work=NSW Government Gazette |page=5253 |date=14 October 2010 |url=http://gazette.legislation.nsw.gov.au/so/download.w3p?id=Gaz_Gazette%20Split%202010_2010-120.pdf |author=. |accessdate=2 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"olgr-abc\">{{Cite episode |title=AVN stripped of charitable status |url=http://mpegmedia.abc.net.au/lateline/video/podcast/r656093_4656980.m4v |series=Lateline |serieslink=Lateline |credits=Stewart, John |network=ABC TV \n|station=ABC1 |location=National |airdate=14 October 2010 |accessdate=2 April 2015|transcript=AVN stripped of charitable status |transcripturl= http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2010/s3038849.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2009, the AVN claimed it had more than 3500 members,<ref name=\"eye\" /> however in a constitutional change voting proxy form published in March 2010, the AVN revealed the actual membership is considerably lower, at around 1867 financial members.<ref name=\"Australian Vaccination Network Proxy form\">{{Cite web |url=http://survey.constantcontact.com/survey/a07e2td9g4rg76ta7c8/a01aeg79o9ud9/questions |title=Australian Vaccination Network Proxy form |author=Dorey, Meryl |date=22 March 2010 |work=AVN |access-date=11 March 2016}}</ref> The AVN is headquartered in [[Bangalow, New South Wales]].\n\nIn February 2010 Dorey announced that she was resigning,<ref name=\"AVN-close\">{{cite web |title=AVN to shut down \u2014 Meryl Dorey resigns as president of the AVN |url=http://youngausskeptics.com/2010/02/avn-to-shut-down-meryl-dorey-resigns-as-president-of-the-avn/ |work=Young Aus Skeptics |date=3 February 2010 |author=Admin |access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref> but held the position of President until 1 January 2013, when she was replaced by Mr Greg Beattie. Ms Dorey remains with the AVN as \"Public Officer and spokesperson\".<ref name=\"president change\">{{cite web |title=AVN-new name, new president |url=http://www.skeptics.com.au/latest/news/avn-told-to-change-unacceptable-name/ |author=. |website=[[Australian Skeptics]] Inc. |date=15 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925031833/http://www.skeptics.com.au/2012/12/15/avn-told-to-change-unacceptable-name/ |archivedate=25 September 2015 |quote=Meryl Dorey, the founder and long-term president of the Australian [anti]Vaccination Network, has announced that she has relinquished her position as president of the organisation, effective January 1 [2013]. Her replacement is Queensland-based AVN board member, Greg Beattie.}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to its website and associated blog AVN published a quarterly magazine called ''Informed Voice'', later renamed ''Living Wisdom'' and offered as a digital publication. ''Living Wisdom'' ceased publication in January 2013. The AVN's paid-for memberships formerly included a quarterly insert called ''Inside Edition''<ref name=nla>{{cite web |url=http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/3597049 |title=NLA catalogue of Informed voice |work=National Library of Australia |accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref> which contained \"12 pages of current news from around the world regarding vaccination\".\n\n===Beliefs===\nThe group is strongly against any form of compulsory vaccination,<ref name=\"ECM\">{{cite news |title=To immunise or not to immunise |author=Moore, Rachel |date=8 July 2009 |page=14 |work=[[Eastern Courier Messenger]] (Adelaide)}}</ref> but Dorey disputes that the group is an anti-vaccine organisation. \"We don't believe we have the right to tell people whether or not to vaccinate\", says Dorey who adds, \"but neither does the government.\"<ref name=\"eye\">{{cite news |title=Eye of the Needle |author=Watt, Amanda |date=18 July 2009 |work=[[The Courier-Mail|QWeekend, The Courier-Mail]] |page=12}}</ref> She says the group is just trying to fill \"the information void\" created by a pro-vaccine government and medical community that ignores negative information.<ref name=\"SMH\" /> Dorey considers herself, \"pro-information and pro-choice\".<ref name=\"Sunrise interview\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ama.com.au/node/583 |title=Sunrise Interview with Dr Trevor Mudge & Meryl Dorey |work=doctors4health - [[Australian Medical Association]] |author=. |date=21 August 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110411071520/http://ama.com.au/node/583|archivedate=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIndependent commentators generally reject these claims and point to numerous errors and distortions in AVN's statements about vaccines.<ref name=\"Whooping\" /> Julie Leask from the [[University of Sydney]], challenges AVN's claim that it is not anti-vaccination, by referring to the numerous examples of anti-vaccination rhetoric published by the AVN.<ref>{{cite thesis |url=https://ses.library.usyd.edu.au/bitstream/2123/12503/1/Julie_Leask_thesis_2002.pdf |first=Julie |last=Leask |pages=42\u201343 |date=2002 |title=Understanding Immunisation Controversies |publisher=University of Sydney |access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref> In 2009, the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] described the AVN as the \"stronghold of the anti-vaccination movement\" in Australia.<ref name=\"Whooping\" /> In 2012 the AVN website promoted the anti-vaccination children's book ''[[Melanie's Marvelous Measles]]''  as well as T-shirts with \"Love Them, Protect Them, Never Inject Them\" printed on them.<ref>{{cite news |author=Dunlop, Rachael |authorlink=Rachael Dunlop|title=Anti-vaccination network told to change its name or be shut down |url=https://theconversation.com/anti-vaccination-network-told-to-change-its-name-or-be-shut-down-11368 |work=The Conversation |date=19 December 2012 |access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"fury\">{{cite news |title=Fury over book promoting measles |url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/qld/a/15801894/fury-over-book-promoting-measles/ |work=Yahoo!News7 |date=10 January 2013 |accessdate=28 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Northern Rivers|NSW Northern Rivers]] region, where the AVN is located, in 2007 had a childhood vaccination rate of only 70% compared to the national average of over 90%.<ref name=\"Maze1\" /> In 2016 a recent National Health Performance Authority report showed the region's average vaccination rate for 5 year olds was reportedly still the lowest in the country at 89.2%.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.northernstar.com.au/news/no-jab-no-pay-for-pensioners-completely-untrue/2943534/ |title='No jab, no pay' for pensioners 'completely untrue' |last=White |first=Leah |date=25 February 2016 |work=[[Northern Star (Australian newspaper)|The Northern Star]] |access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref> The North Coast Assistant Public Health Director warned \"Pockets of unvaccinated people in the region was the cause for the rise and fall in whooping cough cases... because we do not have herd immunity to the illness on the Northern Rivers\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.northernstar.com.au/news/whooping-cough-up-1660-on-northern-rivers/2959507/ |title=Whooping cough outbreak has Northern Rivers on high alert |author=Stevens, Rodney |date=10 March 2016 |work=[[Northern Star (Australian newspaper)|The Northern Star]] |access-date=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian Vaccination-Skeptics Network believes that vaccines contain a variety of toxic ingredients that have no place in the human body.<ref name=\"Whooping\"/> The group argues that these toxins can cause [[autism]], [[ADHD]], brain damage, and cancer, among other serious side effects.<ref name=\"SMH\">{{cite news |title=Vaccine fear campaign investigated |date=16 August 2009 |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |page=27 |url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/vaccine-fear-campaign-investigated-20090815-elsg.html |first=Louise |last=Hall |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004202920/http://www.smh.com.au/national/vaccine-fear-campaign-investigated-20090815-elsg.html |archivedate=4 October 2009}}</ref> In response to medical and scientific research that shows few side effects to most vaccines, Dorey argues that doctors are very hesitant to report adverse reactions and thus the data is highly skewed.<ref name=\"Maze1\">{{cite episode |title=The Immunisation Maze Part 1 (transcript available) |airdate=10 July 2007 |network=[[ABC Radio National]] |series=[[Life Matters]] |author=McMillan, Mel |accessdate=29 January 2016 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/lifematters/the-immunisation-maze-part-1-transcript-available/3231094}}</ref> These claims are false: while minor side effects such as soreness, swelling, and fever are not uncommon, no large scale scientific study has found evidence of more serious reactions<ref name=\"Maze3\">{{cite episode |title=The Immunisation Maze Part 3 (transcript available) |airdate=12 July 2007 |network=[[ABC Radio National]] |series=[[Life Matters]] |author=McMillan, Mel |accessdate=29 January 2016 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/lifematters/the-immunisation-maze-part-3-transcript-available/3245116}}</ref> and the purported link to autism is refuted.<ref name=\"AutismRefutes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.publichealth.org/public-awareness/understanding-vaccines/vaccine-myths-debunked/ |title=Vaccine myths debunked |work=PublicHealth.org |accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nFormer president Meryl Dorey claimed that most doctors are not fully informed about vaccination research and that the medical community as a whole relies on \"[[Cherry picking (fallacy)|selective evidence]]\" to back its argument.<ref name=\"Whooping\" /><ref name=\"prickley\">{{cite news |title=A prickly debate |author=Sheperd, Tory |work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |date=6 November 2009 |page=19}}</ref> She says there is a \"very, very strong effort\" by the government and mainstream medical community to suppress any information that may cause parents to question the safety of vaccines.<ref name=\"eye\"/> Consequently, Dorey argues, doctors often don't adequately warn patients of potential vaccination risks.<ref name=\"Whooping\"/> Several critics have pointed out that AVN itself is guilty of ignoring evidence not favourable to the anti-vaccination point of view<ref name=\"SMH\"/><ref name=\"Whooping\"/><ref name=\"prickley\"/> and the NSW Health Care Complaints Commission (HCCC) found that the AVN routinely ignore information that is not favourable to its anti-vaccination position. The HCCC accused the AVN of deceptively removing selected parts of stories when they report on them, and the misrepresentation of the conclusions of reliable studies. Dorey countered that she was not guilty of selective reporting, and that she \"simply quoted the sections that [she] felt were important\".<ref name=HCCCfinal/> In reality, doctors have access to extensive information on vaccine safety and the medical literature includes all known significant potential adverse reactions.<ref name=\"AAP2\">{{cite web |url=http://www2.aap.org/immunization/families/faq/vaccinestudies.pdf |title=Vaccine Safety: Examine The Evidence |work=[[American Academy of Pediatrics]] |date=4 April 2013 |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816034905/http://www2.aap.org/immunization/families/faq/VaccineStudies.pdf |archivedate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe AVN has also questioned the effectiveness of vaccines. While admitting that infection rates dropped dramatically in the twentieth century, they argue that the change is due in large part to improved hygiene and living conditions.<ref name=\"Maze2\"/> Dorey has argued that infection rates were already on the decline before vaccines were invented<ref name=\"Maze2\"/> and that effectiveness has \"never been scientifically tested.\"<ref name=\"eye\"/> Scientific evidence disputes this opinion by AVsN.<ref name=\"vaccine-2016\">{{cite journal |last1=Hawkes |first1=D |last2=Dunlop |first2=RA |last3=Benhamu |first3=J. |authorlink2=Rachael Dunlop|title=Calls by alternative medicine practitioners for vaccinated vs unvaccinated studies is not supported by evidence |journal=[[Vaccine (journal)|Vaccine]] |volume=34 |issue=28 |pages=3223\u20133224 |date=14 June 2016 |doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2015.12.031 |pmid=27288998 }}</ref> Dorey has also stated that the \"vast majority\" of people who contract disease have previously been vaccinated.<ref name=\"ECM\"/> [[Infectious disease]] [[medical specialist|specialist]] Paul Goldwater acknowledged a few vaccines are not completely effective, but said others were nearly 100% effective. In all cases, he said, \"the benefits certainly outweigh any risks.\"<ref name=\"ECM\"/> The group has also expressed doubts about the [[cost-benefit ratio]] and effectiveness of [[flu vaccine]]s.<ref>{{cite news |title=High cost of kids with flu is avoidable, study shows |author=Price, Sarah |date=30 July 2006 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/high-cost-of-kids-with-flu-is-avoidable-study-shows/2006/07/29/1153816423160.html |accessdate=16 November 2009}}</ref> AVN's arguments are well-known and long debunked anti-vaccine tropes.<ref name=\"kata-vaccine-journal\">Kata, A (2012). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22172504 Anti-vaccine activists, Web 2.0, and the postmodern paradigm--an overview of tactics and tropes used online by the anti-vaccination movement.] in ''[[Vaccine (journal)]], Vol.30, 2012.'' Also cited by [http://www.unicef.org/ceecis/Tracking_anti-vaccine_sentiment_in_Eastern_European_social_media_networks.pdf UNICEF]</ref>\n\nDorey has written that \"passing through a measles infection is sometimes required, for whatever reason, to strengthen some part of a person's vital force\",<ref name=winter06>{{Cite news|last=Dorey |first=Meryl |title=Voodoo Children |website=Informed Voice - AVN |volume=4 |issue=2| page=48 |date=Winter 2006}}</ref> and that diseases such as [[measles]], [[mumps]], [[rubella]] and [[chicken pox]] are benign conditions that do not kill children in industrialized countries.<ref name=\"Maze2\"/> During a studio debate on Channel 7's ''Sunday Night'' current affairs program covering the death of a four-week-old baby from [[whooping cough]], Dorey claimed that no one ever dies from the disease,<ref name=\"SN\">[http://au.tv.yahoo.com/sunday-night/video/-/page/11/#fop  \"Sunday Night\" archive footage for \"Fear and confusion\" (4 May 2009) and \"A mother's choice?\" (26 April 2009)] ''[[Seven Network]] TV''. Archived at [http://www.dilutedthinking.com/avn_sundaynight_pt1.php dilutedthinking.com (pt1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309172657/http://www.dilutedthinking.com/avn_sundaynight_pt1.php |date=9 March 2016 }}, [http://www.dilutedthinking.com/avn_sundaynight_pt2.php dilutedthinking.com pt2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309172409/http://www.dilutedthinking.com/avn_sundaynight_pt2.php |date=9 March 2016 }} & [http://www.dilutedthinking.com/avn_sundaynight_amc.php dilutedthinking.com amc] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309172410/http://www.dilutedthinking.com/avn_sundaynight_amc.php |date=9 March 2016 }}</ref> and described her own children's case of the disease as a \"storm in a teacup\" that was easily handled with natural remedies.<ref name=\"eye\"/> The NSW Health Care Complaints Commission criticised the AVN's position, saying that it \"ignores the risks of exposure to, and the adverse effects of childhood illnesses\".<ref name=HCCCfinal/> Independent data shows that measles causes the most vaccine-preventable deaths of any disease.<ref name=Kabra2013>{{cite journal |last1=Kabra |first1=SK |last2=Lodhra |first2=R |title=Antibiotics for preventing complications in children with measles |journal=[[Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews]] |volume=8 |issue=8 |pages=CD001477 |date=14 August 2013 |pmid=23943263 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD001477.pub4|pmc=7055587 }}</ref> It resulted in about 96,000 deaths in 2013.<ref name=GDB2013>{{cite journal |last1=GBD 2013 Mortality and Causes of Death|first1=Collaborators|title=Global, regional, and national age-sex specific all-cause and cause-specific mortality for 240 causes of death, 1990-2013: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2013.|journal=[[The Lancet]] |date=17 December 2014 |pmid=25530442 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)61682-2 |pmc=4340604 |volume=385 |issue=9963|pages=117\u2013171}}</ref> Before immunization in the United States between three and four million cases occurred each year, and the fatality rate is approximately 0.2% of those infected.<ref name=CDC2012Pink>{{cite book |last=Atkinson |first=William |title=Epidemiology and Prevention of Vaccine-Preventable Diseases |date=2011 |publisher=Public Health Foundation |isbn=9780983263135 |pages=301\u2013323 |edition=12 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/pubs/pinkbook/meas.html |accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref> Most of those who are infected and who die are less than five years old.<ref name=WHO2014>{{cite web |title=Measles Fact sheet N\u00b0286 |author=. |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs286/en/ |website=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=4 February 2015 |date=November 2014}}</ref>\n\nInfectious disease specialist Peter McIntyre<ref name=McIntyreUSYD>{{cite web |title=USYD Profile: Professor Peter McIntyre |date=12 October 2009 |url=http://www.health.usyd.edu.au/people/profiles/P.Mcintyre.php |author=. |work=[[Sydney University]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091012074906/http://www.health.usyd.edu.au/people/profiles/P.Mcintyre.php |archivedate=12 October 2009}}</ref> has accused the group of manipulating research and statistics in order to make its case. \"It's been a real characteristic of the anti-vaccine movement ... [to claim] to be looking very extensively at the scientific evidence,\" says McIntyre, \"[but their conclusions are] really a complete misinterpretation.\"<ref name=\"Whooping\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/09/03/2675448.htm |title=Whooping cough deaths spark vaccination debate |date=3 September 2009 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC TV]] |author= Murray, Kirstin |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726222548/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-09-03/whooping-cough-deaths-spark-vaccination-debate/1416152 |archivedate=26 July 2011}}</ref> [[Paediatrician]] Chris Ingall says that the AVN's efforts are \"negative, destructive and [have] no scientific basis.\"<ref name=\"Whooping\"/> [[Australian Medical Association]] [[South Australia|SA]] state president Andrew Lavender states that groups like the Australian Vaccination-Skeptics Network \"[act] on very little information and ... [pose] a risk to others.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/adelaidenow/story/0,22606,26306408-5006301,00.html |work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |title=Low immunisation behind South Australian whooping cough outbreak |first=Tory |last=Shepherd |date=5 November 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107194622/http://www.news.com.au/adelaidenow/story/0%2C22606%2C26306408-5006301%2C00.html |archivedate=7 November 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDorey argues that scientific studies cannot be trusted because they are usually funded, she claims, by biomedicine and pharmaceutical companies that develop and manufacture vaccine products, and that doctors have \"financial incentives\" to push vaccines.<ref name=\"eye\"/> In fact, paediatricians often lose money on vaccinations.<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2015/02/vaccines-are-profitable-so-what/385214/ |title=Vaccines Are Profitable, So What? |author=Lam, Bourree |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=10 February 2015 |accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"HealthAffairs\">{{cite journal |url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/content/24/3/622.full |title=Why Are Pharmaceutical Companies Gradually Abandoning Vaccines? |journal=[[Health Affairs]] |author=Offit, Paul |volume=24 |issue=3 |pages=622\u201330 | authorlink= Paul Offit| date=1 May 2005 |accessdate=17 April 2015|pmid=15886152 |doi=10.1377/hlthaff.24.3.622 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''The Panic Virus'', by [[Seth Mnookin]]; then AVN President Meryl Dorey signed a petition claiming \"that the \"AIDS industry and the media\" had tricked the public into believing that the HIV virus causes AIDS\".<ref name=panic>{{Cite book |author=Mnookin, Seth |title=The Panic Virus |publisher=Black Inc. |edition=Australian |date=February 2011 |pages=xx\u2013xxii |url=http://sethmnookin.com/the-panic-virus/ |isbn=978-1-86395-518-8|author-link=Seth Mnookin }}</ref>\n\nWhen during a government inquiry in 2015, [[Australian Greens|Greens]] Senator [[Richard Di Natale|Di Natale]] asked AVsN why they still referred to themselves as the \"Australian Vaccination Network\", a name they have been legally instructed to cease using, AVsN member Brett Smith accused Di Natale of being part of a [[Rupert Murdoch|Murdoch]] media conspiracy. Journalist Bernard Keane noted this is the first time anyone had suggested a conspiratorial link between The Greens and a media organisation that has been highly critical of the party.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2015/11/23/discover-this-one-amazing-trick-to-make-politicians-do-what-you-want |title=Discover this one amazing trick to make politicians do what you want! |last=Keane, Bernard |date=23 November 2015 |website=[[Crikey]] |access-date=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, Meryl Dorey compared a [[NSW Health]] policy change requiring immunisation for its workers to [[Nazi concentration camps]] saying \"these are the sorts of [immunisation] tactics you would expect in concentration camps, not the sort of tactics you would expect in the Australian health-care system.\"<ref name=\"NoJob\">{{cite news |title=No immunisation, no job: public health policy |author=Kontominas, Bellinda |work=[[Brisbane Times]] |date=11 April 2007 |page=3 |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/news/national/no-immunisation-no-job-public-health-policy/2007/04/10/1175971099963.html |accessdate=16 November 2009}}</ref> The policy was also opposed by some [[civil libertarian]] and health-care groups,<ref name=\"NoJob\"/> but the [[NSW Nurses' Association]] noted that \"vaccinations have always been compulsory for health workers\" and that the change was only a minimal update to the existing policy.<ref name=\"nswna\">{{cite web |title=Revised Vaccination Policy For Health Workers |work=Union News, [[NSW Nurses' Association]] |url=http://www.nswnurses.asn.au/news/8629.html |author=. |date=10 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004230248/http://www.nswnurses.asn.au/news/8629.html |archivedate= 4 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = '''\"The scaremongering that anti vaccination campaigners engage in extends to the real world, where they threaten and bully the opposition. And what is scarier again is that the AVN is actively trying to stop parents who have lost children to deadly \u2013 but preventable \u2013 diseases, from speaking out about the need to vaccinate.\"'''\n |source = ''Mamamia Magazine'', 27 May 2013.<ref name=mamamia>{{cite news |title=This is how far the anti-vaccination movement will go |work=Mamamia Magazine |last=. |date=27 May 2013 |url=http://www.mamamia.com.au/australian-vaccination-network-bullying-tactics/ |accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref>\n |width  = 30%\n |align  = right\n}}\nThe Australian Vaccination-Skeptics Network has regularly spoken out against vaccine-related positions adopted by the Australian government and defended controversial and discredited research. AVN also distributes literature, sponsors seminars, and collects adverse reaction reports.\n\nIn a 1996 editorial, AVN spoke out against a proposal to add vaccination centres to some shopping centres. Writing on behalf of AVN, Susan Lindberg called the idea \"downright dangerous,\" asking \"what if a baby has a fit or major reaction?\" She also added that parents are under enough pressure to vaccinate already.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jabs in the mall |author=Lindberg, Susan |date=12 April 1996 |work=[[The Australian]]}}</ref>\n\nIn response to a 2002 proposal to extend free vaccination programs, Former AVN president Meryl Dorey argued that the Australian government should first do independent tests of the new vaccines. She said that she had doubts about the accuracy of the existing studies that were \"funded ... by the pharmaceutical companies.\" A member of the government's immunisation advisory group countered that they always assess all available scientific data.<ref name=\"Toddler\">{{cite news |title=Proposal to extend toddler vaccine program causes concern |author=. |date=7 June 2002 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |volume=[Document abcnew0020020607dy67000b5] |quote=But Professor Rubin says they assess all scientific data available. \"The vaccine manufacturers know they've got to through this process and pass all the tests to demonstrate that the vaccine is safe,\" he said.}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2004, AVN spoke out against combination vaccines being considered by health authorities. The organisation claimed that there were too many untested variables and that it was irresponsible to keep combining vaccines without knowing the effects.<ref name=\"Multi\">{{cite news |title=Fears over vaccine cocktail for babies |author=O'Leary, Cathy |date=24 August 2004 |work=[[The West Australian]] |page=1}}</ref> In 2006, Meryl Dorey continued the attack on combined vaccines, claiming it was un-natural, as \"It is a fact that [humans] will only ever contract one disease at a time.\" According to the [[British Medical Journal]] combined vaccines have actually shown reduced side effects,<ref name=\"Multi\"/> and it is quite common for humans to suffer simultaneously from several infections.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.303.6808.935 |last=Openshaw |first=PJ |title=When we sneeze, does the immune system catch a cold? |journal=[[British Medical Journal]] |volume=303 |issue=6808 |pages=935\u2013936 |date=19 October 1991 |pmid=1954412 |pmc=1671377}}</ref>\n\nIn support of AVN's activism, social scientist [[Brian Martin (social scientist)|Brian Martin]] wrote ''Debating vaccination'' in 2011. In a media release the [[University of Wollongong]] stated vaccination \"should be freely debated\" and that the 20,000-word paper was \"intended to assist readers - especially members of the AVN itself\", in ways to respond to criticism and better understand scientific controversy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://media.uow.edu.au/releases/UOW096312.html |title=Vaccination \"should be freely debated\" |author=Goldie, Bernie |date=23 February 2011 |website=Media Releases - [[University of Wollongong]] |access-date=10 April 2016}}</ref> Martin is a former member of the AVN.<ref name=\"australian-conference\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/university-paid-for-anti-vaccine-student-to-attend-conference/story-e6frgcjx-1226811558843 |title=University paid for anti-vaccine student to attend conference |last=Morton |first=Rick |date=28 January 2014|access-date=22 March 2016 |newspaper=[[The Australian]] |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 the group suggested the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|deadly coronavirus]] \"is just the common cold\", and people have been \"fooled\" by a 'fear campaign on the silly sheep media\".<ref name=\"covid 7news\">{{Cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/anti-vaxxers-downplay-common-cold-like-coronavirus-amid-fears-of-forced-vaccinations-c-725089|title=\u2018Just the common cold\u2019: Australian anti-vaxxers move to downplay coronavirus|last=Barnsley|first=Warren|date=2020-03-02|website=7NEWS.com.au|publisher=Seven Network|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.04.07-132646/https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/anti-vaxxers-downplay-common-cold-like-coronavirus-amid-fears-of-forced-vaccinations-c-725089|archive-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Dorey questioned the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] saying: \"Are you being lied to?\" Requesting that followers \"take your phones and pop into the local hospital\" and \"Let us know how crowded it is \u2014 or is not. Is coronavirus really overwhelming our nation or is our nation overwhelming us with lies and killing our economy and us?\"<ref name=\"covid tele\">{{Cite news|last=Hansen|first=Jane|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/coronavirus/antivaxxers-deny-covid19-pandemic-urge-others-to-ignore-isolation-advice/news-story/608d088511f5426df6dc372570d650fe|title=Anti-vaxxers deny COVID-19 pandemic, urge others to ignore isolation advice|date=2020-04-03|work=The Sunday Telegraph|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.04.04-224105/https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/coronavirus/antivaxxers-deny-covid19-pandemic-urge-others-to-ignore-isolation-advice/news-story/608d088511f5426df6dc372570d650fe|archive-date=2020-04-04|location=Sydney NSW|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Adverse reaction reports===\n\nIn December 1996, AVN presented Federal Health Minister [[Michael Wooldridge]] with reports on 150 cases of children claimed to have been injured by vaccines that dated back to 1991; Dorey claimed that the collection of previously unreported reactions represented the largest single collection ever presented to the Australian Government.<ref name=\"JustTheShot\">{{cite news |title=Just The Shot |author=Megan James |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=18 December 1996 |page=9}}</ref> Dorey states that many of the parents involved had previously tried to have their cases looked at, but had been told by health authorities their cases couldn't proceed because the parents lacked necessary documentation.<ref name=\"JustTheShot\"/> Gavin Frost, a government vaccination adviser, said he supported increased medical reporting of vaccine side effects but doubted claims of permanent damage caused by vaccines.<ref name=\"JustTheShot\"/> A published government report shows that over the 33-month period from 1 January 2000 to 30 September 2002, the AVN made a total of 11 unspecified adverse event reports, which equates to approximately one report every three months.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Lawrence |first=Glenda |author2=Robert Menzies |author3=Margaret Burgess |author4=Peter McIntyre |author5=Nicholas Wood |author6=Ian Boyd |author7=Patrick Purcell |author8=David Isaacs |title=Surveillance of adverse events following immunisation: Australia, 2000\u20132002 |volume=27 |issue=3 |pages=307\u201323 |publisher=Australian Government |journal=Department of Health and Ageing |date=September 2003 |url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cda-pubs-cdi-2003-cdi2703-htm-cdi2703a.htm |accessdate=25 April 2010|pmid=14510057 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, the NSW Health Care Complaints Commission criticised the AVN's adverse event reporting system as being \"anecdotal and misleading\".<ref name=HCCCfinal/>\n\n===Views on vaccination incentives===\nIn 1997 Susan Lindberg spoke on behalf of AVN opposing the announcement of a government plan to cut child care and maternity payments to parents who didn't vaccinate their children and to give incentive payments to doctors to give vaccines; she also called for creation of a vaccine registry and adverse event reporting system to be created.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lamb|first1=Eve|title=Call to monitor injections|work=Mercury [Hobart, Tasmania, Australia]|date=27 February 1997|page=9}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2000, Meryl Dorey spoke out against cuts in child care payments for 9000 families who failed to get their children vaccinated.  She called the legislation a type of \"[[civil conscription]]\" and said the program was likely in violation of the [[Constitution of Australia|Constitution]].<ref name=\"AM-ABC-payments\">{{cite news |title=Parents lose childcare payments after failing to immunise |work=[[AM (ABC Radio)]] |author=Willacy, Mark |url=http://www.abc.net.au/am/stories/s123082.htm |date=3 May 2000 |accessdate=20 January 2010}}</ref> Wooldridge responded that the claim was \"nonsense\" because the requirement was \"simply a condition on government financial assistance\" and that families had the choice to accept it or not.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vaccination no-shows lose rebate |author=Probyn, Andrew |work=[[Herald Sun]] |date=4 May 2000 |page=8}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2007, AVN spoke out against the government's practice of giving pediatricians bonus incentives for immunising their patients. Dorey argued that the practice was unethical and led to doctors making decisions based on their pocket book rather than their conscience.<ref name=\"Maze2\">{{cite episode |title=The Immunisation Maze Part 2 (transcript available) |airdate=11 July 2007 |network=[[ABC Radio National]] |series=[[Life Matters]] |author=McMillan, Mel |accessdate=29 January 2016 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/lifematters/the-immunisation-maze-part-2-transcript-available/3245124}}</ref> She would later liken the payment to a bribe noting that doctors aren't paid extra for prescribing antibiotics, for example.<ref name=\"PaymentCancelled\">{{cite news |title=GPs may refuse child vaccinations if bonus cancelled |author=Rehn, Alison |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]] |date=10 October 2008 |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/sydney-news/gps-may-refuse-vaccinations/story-e6freuzi-1111117709109 |accessdate=18 November 2009}}</ref> Dorey further argued that the government began the practice in order to meet [[World Health Organization]] mandates on vaccination percentages and thus was more interested in playing a numbers game rather than doing what was right for the nation's children.<ref name=\"Maze2\"/> The payment was discontinued in October 2008.<ref name=\"PaymentCancelled\"/>\n\nThe NSW Health Care Complaints Commission criticised the AVN for casting medical practitioners in a negative light as \"unethical and untrustworthy without providing any cogent reasons or evidence for making such an assertion\".<ref name=HCCCfinal/>\n\n===Defense of Andrew Wakefield===\n\nIn February 2004, AVN defended [[Andrew Wakefield]]'s 1998 study that suggested a possible link between [[MMR vaccine controversy|autism and MMR]] vaccinations, implying that Wakefield had been treated unfairly and that he lost his job for \"[refusing] to lie.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Doubt cast on vaccine scare |author=Moynihan, Tim |author2=Beaumont, Lucy |work=[[The Age]] |date=22 February 2004 |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/02/21/1077072890932.html |accessdate=16 November 2009 |location=Melbourne}}</ref> Less than a month later, ten of the twelve scientists associated with the study retracted their conclusions.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Murch SH, Anthony A, Casson DH |title=Retraction of an interpretation |journal=Lancet |volume=363 |issue=9411 |page=750 |year=2004 |pmid=15016483 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(04)15715-2|url=http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736%2804%2915715-2/fulltext|display-authors=etal}}</ref> In February 2010, ''[[The Lancet]]'' formally retracted Wakefield's original 1998 article following an independent investigation that concluded Wakefield had been \"dishonest, violated basic research ethics rules and showed a 'callous disregard' for the suffering of children involved in his research\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Harris |first=Gardiner |title=Journal Retracts 1998 Paper Linking Autism to Vaccines |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2 February 2010 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/03/health/research/03lancet.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211052704/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/03/health/research/03lancet.html |archivedate=11 February 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 May 2010, immediately following the [[Struck off|striking-off]] of Mr. Wakefield by the British [[General Medical Council]] for \"gross misconduct\" and \"bringing the medical profession into disrepute\", the AVN continued to support him, issuing the following statement: \"Dr Wakefield knows that he has the love and respect of tens of thousands if not hundreds of thousands of parents around the world. Whether or not the GMC which is stacked with corrupt influences strikes him off is of no consequence. He will continue his work and autistic families everywhere will benefit as a result.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr Wakefield Knows... |work=Australian Vaccination Network |date=24 May 2010 |url=http://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=129116743767690&id=55142201924 |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129171047/http://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=129116743767690&id=55142201924 |archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref> In a statement following the ruling, Wakefield said \"I never made the claim at the time, nor do I still make the claim that MMR is a cause of autism.\"<ref>{{Cite news |title=Andrew Wakefield struck off over MMR scandal |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] (UK) |date=24 May 2010 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/7758704/Andrew-Wakefield-struck-off-over-MMR-scandal.html |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527033555/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/7758704/Andrew-Wakefield-struck-off-over-MMR-scandal.html |archivedate=27 May 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Actions against the Australian Measles Control Campaign===\n\nPrior to the commencement of the 1998 [[Australian Measles Control Campaign]], the AVN initiated a campaign against it, for example accusing the Federal Government of using bullying tactics, overstating the effectiveness of the vaccine and understating the potential side effects.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farah|first1=Farouque|title=$30m goes into fight to end measles|work=Age [Melbourne, Australia]|date=10 July 1998|page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Olsson K|first1=K|title=Point of Contention|work=Courier-Mail [Brisbane, Queensland, Australia]|date=14 July 1998|page=25}}</ref> In July AVN said that they were instigating a [[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]] [[injunction]] against the campaign, to try to force it to change the information booklet and to simplify the forms required to obtain an exemption.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hele|first1=Michelle|title=Legal bid to change vaccine campaign|work=Courier-Mail [Brisbane, Queensland, Australia]|date=24 July 1998|page=9}}</ref> The AVN's statements prompted the Federal Minister for Health to describe the group as \"deceitful crackpots\",<ref name=\"wooldridge\"/> while the results of the campaign showed there were just 89 adverse reactions, and that the campaign resulted in a large increase of measles and rubella immunity levels.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Let's Work Together to Beat Measles: A Report on Australia's Measles Control Campaign |place=Canberra |author=NCIRS-VPD |work=Commonwealth of Australia |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-642-44682-4}} Available via [https://web.archive.org/web/20070831083544/http://www.immunise.health.gov.au/internet/immunise/publishing.nsf/Content/B53AE753F48C4908CA25719D00183413/%24File/archive-measles-letsworktogether.pdf Internet Archive of Australia Department of Health webpage]</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Gilbert |first=GL |author2=Escott RG |author3=Gidding HF |author4=Turnbull FM |author5=Heath TC |author6=McIntyre PB |author7=Burgess MA. |title=Impact of the Australian Measles Control Campaign on immunity to measles and rubella |journal=Epidemiology and Infection Journal |volume=127 |issue=2 |pages=297\u2013303 |date=October 2001 |pmid=11693507 |pmc=2869749| doi=10.1017/s0950268801005830}}</ref>\n\nAt a Perth anti-vaccination seminar on 1 June 2010, Dorey was critical of the government's introduction of the [[measles vaccine]] to Australia in 1970, saying \"We introduced a vaccine for a disease which was killing almost nobody and one has to ask, why?\"<ref name=PerthSeminar1>{{Cite conference |author1=Dorey, Meryl |author2-link=Judith Wilyman PhD controversy |author2=Wilyman, Judy |title=AVN Anti-Vaccination Seminar Perth |date=1 June 2010 |location=[[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]] |url=http://media.buzzsprout.com/6152.mp3 |archive-format= mp3 audio |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308221535/http://media.buzzsprout.com/6152.mp3 |archivedate=8 March 2012}}</ref> Mortality data shows that during the decade 1966 to 1975, there were 146 certified deaths from measles in Australia<ref name=WHOmeasles>{{cite journal |last=Heywood |first=Anita |author2=Gidding, Heather F |author3=Riddell, Michaela A |author4=McIntyre, Peter B |author5=MacIntyrea, C Raina |author6=Kelly, Heath A. |title=Elimination of endemic measles transmission in Australia |journal=[[World Health Organization]] |volume=87 |issue=1 |pages=64\u201371 |year=2009 |pmid=19197406 |pmc=2649598 |doi=10.2471/blt.07.046375 }}</ref> while in the decade 1996 to 2005, there were zero deaths directly attributed to measles, and one death due to the measles complication [[Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis|SSPE]].<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Vaccine Preventable Diseases and Vaccination Coverage in Australia, 2003 to 2005 |journal=Communicable Diseases Intelligence (CDI) |volume=31| issue=Supplement |date=June 2007 |author=Dept of Health |url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cda-cdi31suppl.htm~cda-cdi31suppl-3.htm~cda-cdi31suppl-3f.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080801074716/http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cda-cdi31suppl.htm~cda-cdi31suppl-3.htm~cda-cdi31suppl-3f.htm |archivedate=1 August 2008 }}</ref> The decline in mortality is attributed to Australia's high measles vaccination rates achieving the elimination of endemic measles transmission in Australia.<ref name=WHOmeasles/>\n\nIn 2014 Australia was declared by the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] as having eliminated local strains of measles. But as of 2015/16 deadly measles cases had returned and this was no longer the case.<ref name=TheAdvocateTas>{{cite news |title=Risks far too great to ignore immunisation |url=http://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/3867937/risks-far-too-great-to-ignore-immunisation/ |work=[[The Advocate (Tasmania)]] |date=26 April 2016 |access-date=26 April 2016 |author=.}}</ref>\n\n===Campaign against the meningococcal vaccine===\n\nThe AVN campaigned against the introduction of a [[meningococcal vaccine]] to Australia in 2002. Meryl Dorey accused the government of wasting {{AUD}}41 million on the vaccination program, claimed that the vaccine had shown a large number of adverse reactions in the United Kingdom and had never been tested for effectiveness. However the vice-president of the AMA, Trevor Mudge, refuted her claims, pointing out that [[meningococcal disease]] is extremely dangerous and that \"Vaccination really is the only strategy for this condition that is likely to work\". He said the vaccine had been extensively tested and contrary to Dorey's claims had been found to be safe and highly effective in the UK.<ref name=\"Sunrise interview\"/><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Tunkel |first=Allan |title=Efficacy of meningococcal serogroup C conjugate vaccine in teenagers and toddlers in England |journal=Current Infectious Disease Reports |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=350\u20131 |publisher=Current Medicine Group LLC |location=UK |year=2001 |issn=1523-3847 |doi=10.1007/s11908-001-0074-8 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last= Miller |first=E |author2=Salisbury D |author3=Ramsay M. |title=Planning, registration, and implementation of an immunisation campaign against meningococcal serogroupC disease in the UK: a success story |journal=[[Vaccine (journal)|Vaccine]] |volume=20 Supp 1 |pages=58\u201367 |year=2001 |pmid=11587814 |doi=10.1016/S0264-410X(01)00299-7}}</ref> During an online debate covering meningococcal vaccination in 2005, Australian infectious disease specialist Peter McIntyre<ref name=\"McIntyreUSYD\"/> warned parents \"not to be fooled by the limited and biased information from [the] AVN website.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=McIntyre |first=Peter |title=Meningococcal Vaccine forum |work=[[ABC TV (Australia)]] |date=12 July 2005 |url=http://www2b.abc.net.au/4corners/forum/archives/archive104/newposts/60/topic60582.shtm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050914025411/http://www2b.abc.net.au/4corners/forum/archives/archive104/newposts/60/topic60582.shtm |archivedate=14 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe rate of invasive meningococcal disease in Australia fell by more than 60% between 2002 (when vaccination commenced) and 2009, after doubling during the previous decade.<ref>{{cite web |title=Summary tables that include all diseases |author=National Notifiable Diseases Surveillance System |work=Australian [[Department of Health and Ageing]] |date=1 June 2010 |url=http://www9.health.gov.au/cda/Source/CDA-index.cfm |accessdate=1 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=Vaccine Preventable Diseases and Vaccination Coverage in Australia, 2003 to 2005 - Meningococcal |journal=Communicable Diseases Intelligence Journal |volume=31 |pages=Supplement |publisher=National Centre for Immunisation Research and Surveillance and the Australian Institute of Health and Welfare on behalf of the Australian Government Department of Health and Ageing |date=June 2007 |url=http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cda-cdi31suppl.htm~cda-cdi31suppl-3.htm~cda-cdi31suppl-3g.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019165934/http://www.health.gov.au/internet/main/publishing.nsf/Content/cda-cdi31suppl.htm~cda-cdi31suppl-3.htm~cda-cdi31suppl-3g.htm |archivedate=19 October 2010}}</ref> Mortality data from the UK shows that meningococcal deaths decreased from 67 to 5 in the two years following implementation of the vaccine. The NSW HCCC criticised the AVN for selectively using information to support its position, when there is no evidence to support their claims, and that the evidence suggests that the most effective meningococcal strategy is to widely vaccinate.<ref name=HCCCfinal/>\n\n===Campaign against the pertussis (whooping cough) vaccine===\n\nFollowing the death of four-week-old Dana McCaffery from [[Pertussis|pertussis (whooping cough)]] in March 2009, and the subsequent government campaigns to improve pertussis immunisation,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Brian Robins and Louise|title=Immunisation boost to battle whooping cough|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/lifestyle/diet-and-fitness/immunisation-boost-to-battle-whooping-cough-20090904-fbik.html|work=Canberra Times|date=5 September 2009}}</ref> the AVN launched a campaign against the pertussis vaccine, using the death of the child in the campaign materials, claiming that the she did not die from pertussis.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Benson|first1=Kate|title=Anti-vaccine group a threat|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/antivaccine-group-a-threat-20100726-10smn.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=27 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=SHoutrage>{{cite news|last1=Gray|first1=Steve|title=Outrage over campaign after baby's death|url=http://www.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/outrage-over-campaign-after-babys-death-20100727-10ttb.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref><ref name=HCCClateline/><ref name=\"antivax-trolls\">{{cite news |last=Hansen |first=Jane |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/opinion/jane-hansen-antivax-trolls-attack-baby-rileys-grieving-parents/news-story/fa396fee36d7038d8da958b42aa608b5 |title=Anti-vax trolls attack baby Riley's grieving parents |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]] |date=11 April 2015 |accessdate=18 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe AVN's public campaign against the pertussis vaccine began with an article in the May 2009 issue of ''Living Wisdom'' written by Meryl Dorey, which questioned the safety and effectiveness of the vaccine and the dangers of whooping cough itself. Critics pointed out that Dorey's article contained numerous errors of fact and omission.<ref name=panic/><ref name=HCCCfinal>{{Cite web|url=http://www.quackwatch.com/03HealthPromotion/immu/hccc.pdf|title=Complainant: Mr Ken McLeod, Mrs Toni & Mr David McCaffery. Respondent: Meryl Dorey/A.V.N. |author=NSW HCCC|date=7 July 2010|website=Quack Watch|access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref> While the article correctly stated that [[Sweden]] had previously withdrawn pertussis vaccination in 1979 due to research showing it was ineffective, she failed to reveal that the vaccine then used in Sweden was different to the effective vaccine used in other countries such as Australia,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Pertussis Vaccine Case |work=The [[University of Bergen]] (Norway) |url=http://www.ethica.uib.no/pertussis.htm |date=7 May 2010 |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527003626/https://www.docdroid.net/T3uxLH2/ethica-uib-no-pertussis-htm.rtf.html |archivedate=27 May 2016 }}</ref> nor did she reveal that Sweden reintroduced pertussis vaccination in 1996 and this had resulted in huge incidence reduction, with cases falling by 80-90% within 3 years.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Olin |first=P |author2=Hallander, H.O. |title=Marked Decline in Pertussis Followed Re-Introduction of Pertussis Vaccination in Sweden |journal=The Eurosurveillance Journal |volume=4 |issue=12 |publisher=Swedish Institute for Infectious Disease Control |date=1 December 1999 |url=http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=84 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503235550/http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=84 |archivedate=3 May 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the article, Dorey claims that \"Whooping Cough is not a vaccine-preventable disease\". Critics point out that evidence has shown that the acellular vaccine is 84% efficacious,<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Greco |first=D |author2=Salmaso S |author3=Mastrantonio P |author4=Giuliano M |author5=Tozzi AE |author6=Anemona A |title=A Controlled Trial of Two Acellular Vaccines and One Whole-Cell Vaccine against Pertussis |journal=The New England Journal of Medicine |volume=334 |issue=6 |pages=341\u20138 |year=1996 |doi=10.1056/NEJM199602083340601 |pmid=8538704 |display-authors=etal|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/e36d2b202b25d4f18b30e2200d2a0a269588dae5 }}</ref> and prevents 99.8% of infant hospital admissions after a completing a full course of three doses of the vaccine.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Juretzko |first=P |author2=von Kries R |author3=Wirsing von Konig CH |author4=Weil J |author5=Giani G. | title=Effectiveness of Acellular Pertussis Vaccine assessed by Hospital-Based Active Surveillance in Germany |journal=Journal of Clinical Infectious Diseases |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=162\u20137 |location=Germany |year=2002 |doi=10.1086/341027 |pmid=12087522 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nTheir campaign against the vaccine continued during two Channel 7 [[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|''Sunday Night'']] television programs, where Dorey made the claim that \"no-one ever dies of Whooping Cough\".<ref name=\"SN\"/> During the debates, the facts surrounding the death of Dana McCaffery from whooping cough were disputed by Dorey and other AVN members, and it was alleged that the infant's parents had received [[hatemail]] from AVN supporters for their public pro-vaccination stance following the death of their daughter. The filming of this program was the catalyst for the formation of the ''Stop the AVN'' group.<ref name=savn>{{cite web |title=Stop the Australian Vaccination Network |work=[[Young Australian Skeptics]] |last=Raffaele |first=Daniel |url=http://www.youngausskeptics.com/2009/08/australian-vaccination-network/ |date=4 August 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023211000/http://www.youngausskeptics.com/2009/08/australian-vaccination-network/ |archivedate=23 October 2010}}</ref>{{primary-inline|date=March 2017}}\n\nAVN members continued to harass the McCafferys through to July 2010 by sending emails, letters and AVN brochures to the family.<ref name=SHoutrage/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cannane|first1=Steve|title=Anti-vaccine group accused of harassing parents|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-07-12/anti-vaccine-group-accused-of-harassing-parents/901904|work=ABC News|date=12 July 2010|language=en-AU}}</ref> Former AVN president Meryl Dorey wrote another blog disputing the McCafferys' version of events, the treatments and effects Dana suffered and the diagnosis of pertussis. Dana's mother attempted to get the government intervene, to stop the harassment.<ref name=SHoutrage/> In a subsequent television interview for ABC ''[[Lateline]]'', Dorey admitted she had accused the McCafferys of \"turning their daughter into a martyr because she supposedly died of whooping cough\".<ref name=HCCClateline/>\n\nIn 2012 the AVN continued to target the McCafferys. AVN member and [[University of Wollongong]] researcher [[Judith Wilyman PhD controversy|Judy Wilyman]] was published on AVN's website accusing the State Government of using the imagery of four-week-old Dana's death to push the vaccine stating it was the \"Government and the media who have been using the McCafferys to promote a vaccine\". She also questioned whether the McCafferys had been paid to promote the whooping cough vaccine.<ref name=\"mercury-grieving\"/> The McCaffery family vigorously denied these claims.<ref name=\"mercury-grieving\">{{cite news |title=Vaccine row: grieving parents slam researcher |work=The [[Illawarra Mercury]] |date=10 June 2012 |url=http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/270596/vaccine-row-grieving-parents-slam-researcher/ |accessdate=2 February 2016 |author=Cydonee, Mardon}}</ref> In March 2016 Wilyman continued to repeat that such child deaths are \"anecdotal\"<ref name=mamamia2012>{{cite news |author=Reasonable, Hank |url=http://www.mamamia.com.au/anti-vaccination/ |title=The despicable cruelty of the anti-vaccination movement |work=Mamamia Magazine |date=24 April 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=wily2016/> and provoke the parents of the deceased children saying they are \"promoting the death of their child to whooping cough, and lobby groups ... have provided awards to these parents for their efforts [and] they receive financial rewards from pro-vaccine lobby groups for their efforts\".<ref name=wily2016>{{Cite web |url=http://us8.campaign-archive1.com/?u=f20605fde3732e41929f4a3f2&id=2bb73f0574 |title=Newsletter 100 Australian Politicians presenting Myths about Vaccination |last=Wilyman, Judith |date=March 2016 |website=Vaccination Decisions |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160620092459/https://www.docdroid.net/gu8CSxi/archiveis-gfapc.docx.html |archive-date=20 June 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Campaign against the swine flu vaccine===\n\nIn September 2009, AVN campaigned against the [[2009 flu pandemic vaccine|swine flu vaccine]], calling it \"madness\" to use a vaccine which they claimed was \"laden with toxic mercury.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Swine flu vaccine to cost $6m |author=Rudra, Natasha |date=20 September 2009 |work=[[The Canberra Times]] |page=A.14}}</ref> Dorey further argued that more testing was needed on the vaccine before it was offered to the public and that it could prove to be more dangerous than the flu itself.<ref name=\"ABC Swine\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/09/19/2690820.htm |title=Lobby group urges more swine flu vaccine tests |date=19 September 2009 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126161116/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/09/19/2690820.htm |archivedate=26 November 2009 | url-status=live}}</ref> She told the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] that the [[2009 flu pandemic|swine flu]] should be treated no differently from the [[seasonal flu]] and that the government was wasting money by spending over a hundred million dollars on the vaccine.<ref name=\"ABC Swine\"/> Dorey's claims were rejected by the [[Australian Medical Association]] and other medical experts.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vaccine claims rejected |author=Egan, Carmel |date=20 September 2009 |work=[[The Age]] |page=7 |url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/vaccine-claims-rejected-20090919-fw56.html |location=Melbourne |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215093735/http://www.theage.com.au/national/vaccine-claims-rejected-20090919-fw56.html |archivedate=15 December 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-vaccination seminars and public talks===\n\nIn May 2010 the AVN announced that they would be hosting a seminar in [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], Western Australia, to be held at the [[Uniting Church]] In The City (UCIC) on 14 May. However following a campaign by members of the Church, the medical community and members of the ''Stop the AVN'' group, the Church announced that they would not allow the AVN to use their premises for the seminar, as they were \"concerned that there may be a public perception that the UCIC does not support childhood vaccinations due to the AVN seminar being held at UCIC's rooms\".<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Cancelation of Australian Vaccination Network event |work=Uniting Church in the City |date=13 May 2010 |url=http://www.gtp.com.au/ucic/inewsfiles/AVN%20statement%20on%20letterhead%20docx.pdf |location=Perth |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314154242/http://www.gtp.com.au/ucic/inewsfiles/AVN%20statement%20on%20letterhead%20docx.pdf |archivedate=14 March 2012}}</ref> The AVN rescheduled and relocated the event for 1 June at the State Library of WA. The decision by the Library to allow the AVN to use their premises was widely criticised by the medical community and politicians, with the president of the Australian Medical Association saying he \"was worried the use of the venue could give the group credibility\"<ref name=Perth>{{Cite news |last=Taylor |first=Robert |author2=O'Leary, Cathy |title=Anti-vaccine forum causes row |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=1 June 2010 |url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/a/-/breaking/7323001/anti-vaccine-forum-causes-row/ |accessdate=5 June 2010}}</ref> and the Shadow Arts Minister, John Hyde, saying \"Why should a group that endangers the lives of WA children be allowed to speak and promote their cause at a taxpayer-funded venue dedicated to learning?\"<ref name=Perth/> Two days after the event, [[Fiona Stanley]] [[Order of Australia|AC]] was interviewed by Perth Radio about the seminar, describing the views presented by the AVN as \"bizarre\", and \"so misinformed that it is scary\".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Professor Stanley Vaccination (mp3 audio) |url=http://www.rtrfm.com.au/stories/type/current/category/health/2154 |series=Morning Magazine |station=[[6RTR (FM)]] |location=Perth |airdate=3 June 2010 |author=(Interviewer), Mary |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308072740/http://www.rtrfm.com.au/dreamgirl/filesend/11907/vaccination.mp3 |archivedate=8 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn Dec 2011, organisers of the [[Woodford Folk Festival]] were criticised for inviting Meryl Dorey to speak.<ref>{{cite news |last=Miles |first=Janelle |title=Anti-vaccination activist Meryl Dorey needles opponents of her speaking at Woodford Folk festival |newspaper=[[The Courier-Mail]] |location=Brisbane |publisher=News Ltd |date=15 December 2011 |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/anti-vaccine-activist-needles-opponents/story-e6freon6-1226222416563 |accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dunlop |first=Rachael |authorlink=Rachael Dunlop|title=Meryl Dorey at Woodford Folk Festival: a hazard to your child's health? |work=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] |date=December 2011 |url=http://theconversation.edu.au/meryl-dorey-at-woodford-folk-festival-a-hazard-to-your-childs-health-4678 |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> The Queensland Health Minister [[Geoff Wilson (Australian politician)|Geoff Wilson]] advised attendees \"not to take [Dorey's] nonsense too seriously\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Minister needles folk fest speaker |newspaper=[[Sunshine Coast Daily]] |date=16 December 2011 |url=http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/story/2011/12/16/minister-needles-folk-fest-speaker/ |accessdate=18 December 2011 |author=.}}</ref> The Australian Medical Association described the group's views as \"dangerous\", and said organisers \"had a responsibility to add speakers who could provide the medically approved side of the argument\" so the audience were aware of \"the risk of the information being presented [by Dorey]\". Community pressure intensified resulting in Andreas Suhrbier, head of the immunovirology laboratory at the [[Queensland Institute of Medical Research]], to appear and field questions from the audience.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Vaccination debate gets heated at Woodford Folk Festival |work=[[The Courier-Mail]] |author=Brennan, Rose |date=30 December 2011 |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/its-a-tough-gig-talking-science/story-e6freoof-1226232940546 |accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Objection to \"No Jab No Pay/Play\"===\nAVN have promoted the [[Church of Conscious Living]], described in the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' as a \"fake\", and in the ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Telegraph]]'' as a \"sham\" church set up to provide spurious religious exemptions from vaccination.<ref name=\"SMH-church\">{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/health/antivaccination-group-encourages-parents-to-join-fake-church-20150128-12zcrc.html |title=Anti-vaccination group encourages parents to join fake church |author= Medew, Julia |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=28 January 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tele-church\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/real-churches-denounce-cult-of-anti-vaccine/story-fni0cx12-1226660589245 |title=Real churches denounce cult of anti-vaccine |author=Hansen, Jane |date=9 June 2013 |work=[[The Sunday Telegraph (Sydney)]] |accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> The NSW Health Minister said she was \"alarmed that a 'religion' would be created to thwart an important public health initiative.\"<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/anti-vaccine-zealots-form-sham-church/story-fni0cx12-1226653266194 |title=Anti-vaccine zealots form sham church |author=Wood, Alicia |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]] |date=20 May 2013 |accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> In April 2015 the \"no jab, no pay\" policy was introduced and the [[Tony Abbott|Abbott]] Federal Government made it more difficult for people to object to vaccination on religious grounds, and required that religions register their objection to vaccination.<ref name=\"GuardianCL\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/12/parents-who-refuse-to-vaccinate-children-to-be-denied-childcare-rebates-reports |title=Parents who refuse to vaccinate children to be denied childcare rebates |author=Hurst, Daniel |work=The [[Guardian Australia]] |date=11 April 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tele-abbott\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/opinion/claire-harvey-saving-babies-is-one-legacy-of-tony-abbott-that-nobody-can-jab-at/news-story/03a77c7be96f4de554c3d4becfd7b03a |title=Saving babies is one legacy of Tony Abbott that nobody can jab at |author=Harvey, Claire |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]] |date=20 March 2016 |accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> The policy officially came into effect in January 2016 and reportedly \"sparked a rush on vaccines as parents fear missing out\" on Family Tax Benefit Part A supplement and childcare subsidies.<ref name=\"btsparks\">{{cite news |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/nsw/federal-governments-no-jab-no-pay-law-sparks-run-on-vaccines-20160219-gmyusd.html |title=Federal government's 'no jab, no pay' law sparks run on vaccines |author=Marriner, Cosmina |date=20 February 2016 |work=[[Brisbane Times]] |accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAVsN president Tasha David and former president Meryl Dorey both appeared on an \"expert panel\" at a February 2016 anti vaccine event in [[Mullumbimby]] (which has the lowest vaccination rates in Australia) at which other ways of evading no jab no play/pay rules were discussed, including falsely claiming \"hypersensitivity\" to [[gelatin]] or [[yeast]], in order to obtain medical exemption. It was reported in ''The Daily Telegraph'' that Tasha David and Meryl Dorey were at the event to \"prove that Australia was a testing ground for the rest of the world\".<ref name=\"Telegraph-Mullumbimby\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/opinion/jane-hansen-an-alternative-universe-where-vaccines-are-the-villain-not-the-hero/news-story/c70afbec565cc9ed4ad8bb0f560776f3| title=An alternative universe where vaccines are the villain, not the hero |author=Hansen, Jane |date=28 February 2016| work=[[The Sunday Telegraph (Sydney)]] |access-date=28 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016 the AVsN announced its intention to legally challenge the [[Government of Australia|Federal]] 'no jab no pay' laws,<ref name=\"echonetdaily2016\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.echo.net.au/2016/03/no-jab-no-pay-penalties-from-next-week/ |title=No jab no pay penalties from next week |author=Dobney, Chris |date=15 March 2016 |work=[[Byron Shire Echo|Echonetdaily]] |access-date=15 March 2016 }}</ref> with the return of spokesperson Meryl Dorey stating \"[w]hat the government is doing is unconstitutional, immoral and illegal, and they need to be shown the error of their ways\".<ref name=\"Legal_Action\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/health/antivaccination-lobby-flags-high-court-challenge-to-no-jab-no-pay/news-story/8a26375fbc7cf11002ca8a8b23e363ea |title=Anti-vaccination lobby flags High Court challenge to 'no jab, no pay' |last=Berkovic |first=Nicola |date=30 March 2016 |work=[[The Australian]] |url-access=subscription  |access-date=11 April 2016}}</ref> In one announcement AVsN falsely stated that [[Royal Australian College of General Practitioners]] and the National Centre for Immunisation Research & Surveillance also opposed the 'No Jab No Pay' legislation. Both organisations promptly rejected AVsN's claim and clarified they supported the legislation.<ref name=\"nstar\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.northernstar.com.au/news/anti-vaxxers-set-to-challenge-no-jab-no-pay-in-hig/2979274/ |title=Royal College of GPs refutes anti-vaxxers claims |author=Broome, Hamish |date=29 March 2016 |work=[[Northern Star (Australian newspaper)|The Northern Star]] |access-date=29 March 2016}}</ref> By December AVsN had raised AUD$152,000 toward the legal challenge, then on Christmas Day announced it was dropping the legal action, citing a \"poor chance of success\".<ref name=\"Drop_Legal_Action\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/health/antivax-advocates-quietly-ditch-law-suit-against-government/news-story/1a372e80f7a77d82859538b7798491ce |title=Anti-vax advocates quietly ditch law suit against government |last=Loussikian |first=Kylar |date=26 December 2016 |work=[[The Australian]] |url-access=subscription  |access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Complaints, investigations and criticisms==\n\nThe AVN has been the subject of several complaints to (and investigations by) Government departments and medical authorities. Medical professionals, scientists and other proponents of vaccination are highly critical of the AVN.\n\n===NSW Health Care Complaints Commission (HCCC)===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:HCCC NSW - PUBLIC WARNING AVN 2010.png|thumb|right|HCCC NSW - Public Warning About The Australian Vaccination Network (AVN) 26 July 2010.]] -->\nIn August 2009, Ken McLeod filed a complaint against AVN with the New South Wales Health Care Complaints Commission.<ref name=\"SMH\"/> The complaint, which was supported by the group ''[[Australian Skeptics]]'', said that the organisation was in breach of the Health Care Complaints Act because it made \"unsubstantiated health claims based on 'conspiracy theories', pseudo-scientific evidence and debunked research.\" The complaint was also supported by Australian entrepreneur [[Dick Smith (entrepreneur)|Dick Smith]].<ref name=\"Tim Brunero\">{{cite news |title=Dick Smith pushes immunisation |work =[[Macquarie National News]] |author=Brunero, Tim |date=6 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the complaint, the AVN submitted a 27-page document which argued that they are not actively providing health care service and therefore are not under the jurisdiction of the Health Care Complaints Commission.<ref>{{cite web |title=AVN e-newsletter, October 2008 |url=http://www.antivaxxers.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/avn_hccc_amended.pdf |first=Meryl |last=Dorey |work=AVN |accessdate=27 October 2009}}</ref> Dorey called the complaint vexatious and a nuisance tactic.<ref name=\"abc-sceptics\">{{cite news |url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-08-06/sceptics-take-aim-at-vaccination-doubters/1381130 |title=Sceptics take aim at vaccination doubters |work=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |date=6 August 2009 |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110121103/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-08-06/sceptics-take-aim-at-vaccination-doubters/1381130 |archivedate=10 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nTom Sidwell, a [[Monash University]] [[Immunology]] student, conducted a review of the sources and information provided in the AVN's HCCC reply. He submitted to the HCCC that all of the sources quoted by Dorey in the reply were either not from [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] journals as Dorey had claimed, or did not actually support the conclusions she was attributing to them.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sidwell |first=Tom |title=Analysis of AVN Articles |date=1 March 2010 |url=http://www.antivaxxers.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/Analysis-of-AVN-articles-by-Tom-Sidwell.pdf |work=HCCC Reference 09/1695 |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sidwell |first=Tom |work=HCCC Reference 09/1695 |title=Critical Analysis of Immune Suppression Articles |date=18 March 2010 |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/57654694/Second-Analysis-Critical-Analysis-of-Immune-suppression-Articles-V2 |format=PDF |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225044612/http://www.scribd.com/doc/57654694/Second-Analysis-Critical-Analysis-of-Immune-suppression-Articles-V2 |archivedate=25 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sidwell |first=Tom |title=Source of AVN References |date=7 March 2010 |url=http://www.antivaxxers.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/Source-of-AVN-references.pdf |work=HCCC Reference 09/1695 |accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Sidwell |first=Tom |title=An analysis of AVN references - Part 4 |date=25 March 2010 |url=http://www.antivaxxers.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/Fourth-analysis-Misc-references-Release-copy.pdf |work=HCCC Reference 09/1695 |accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> In an article published in the ''Journal of the Australian Skeptics'', Sidwell wrote:\n:\"The collection of references is, on the whole, laughable. At best she hasn't read the papers she cites and includes them out of ignorance, and at worst she is being deliberately deceptive.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Sidwell |first=Tom |title=The truth behind the AVN Claims |work=Australian Skeptics |date=17 March 2010 |url=http://www.skeptics.com.au/latest/blog/the-truth-behind-the-avn-claims/ |accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n====HCCC ruling====\n\nThe HCCC concluded their investigation into the AVN in July 2010. The Commission determined that \"the health education service provided by the Australian Vaccination Network on its website provides misleading and inaccurate information on the subject of vaccination\".<ref name=HCCCfinal/>\n\nIn addition, the Commission found that the AVN \"misleads readers by using reliable and peer-reviewed research, but quoting selectively from it, often in contradiction to the conclusions or findings of the studies themselves\".<ref name=HCCCfinal/>\n\nThe Commission ordered the AVN to permanently place the following information in a prominent place on their website within 14 days:\n\n* The Australian Vaccination Network's purpose is to provide information against vaccination in order to balance what it believes is the substantial amount of pro-vaccination information available elsewhere;\n* The information provided should not be read as medical advice; and\n* The decision about whether or not to vaccinate should be made in consultation with a health care provider.<ref name=HCCCfinal/>\n\nFollowing the AVN's refusal to display the notice, on 26 July 2010 the HCCC issued a public warning about the group stating\n: \"The AVN's failure to include a notice on its website of the nature recommended by the Commission may result in members of the public making improperly informed decisions about whether or not to vaccinate, and therefore poses a risk to public health and safety.\"<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Public Warning About The Australian Vaccination Network (AVN) |work=NSW Health Care Complaints Commission |date=26 July 2010 |url=http://www.hccc.nsw.gov.au/Publications/Media-Releases/PUBLIC-WARNING-/default.aspx |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718000811/http://www.hccc.nsw.gov.au/Publications/Media-Releases/PUBLIC-WARNING-/default.aspx |archivedate=18 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe NSW HCCC's ruling was further supported by the Chief Medical Officer of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], who agreed that the AVN \"should make it clear what their views are and if it's an extreme view about a certain topic it should be clear that it is their view and that they're not speaking on behalf of for example the medical profession\".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Top doctor backs disclaimer for anti-vaccination site |url=http://mpegmedia.abc.net.au/news/audio/twt/201007/20100713-twt-10-vaccines.mp3 |series=The World Today \n|credits=Hall, Eleanor; Lauder, Simon \n|network=ABC \n|station= Radio National \n|location=Australia (National) \n|airdate=13 July 2010 \n|transcript=Top doctor backs disclaimer for anti-vaccination site \n|transcripturl=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2010/s2952217.htm}}</ref>\n\n====Supreme Court appeal====\n\nThe AVN appealed the HCCC ruling to the NSW Supreme Court, arguing that the HCCC does not have jurisdiction over Meryl Dorey or the AVN.<ref name=HCCClateline>{{Cite episode |title=Anti-vaccination group accused of harassing parents |url=http://mpegmedia.abc.net.au/lateline/video/podcast/r599716_3894917.m4v |series=[[Lateline]] |credits=Cannane, Steve |network=ABC TV |station=ABC1 |location=National |airdate=12 July 2010 |transcript=Anti-vaccination group accused of harassing parents |transcripturl=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2010/s2951651.htm}}</ref><ref name=SupCourt>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caselaw.nsw.gov.au/decision/54a636e03004de94513d94f7 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20160517054015/https://www.caselaw.nsw.gov.au/decision/54a636e03004de94513d94f7 |archive-date=17 May 2016 |title=Australian Vaccination Network Inc v Health Care Complaints Commission [2012] NSWSC 110 |last=Supreme Court, NSW |date=24 February 2012 |website=New South Wales Caselaw |url-status=dead|access-date=28 March 2017 }}</ref> In February 2012, the court ruled that the AVN is a health care provider, and therefore the HCCC does have jurisdiction over their activities. However, it ruled that the original complaints to the HCCC about the AVN were invalid because the complaints did not include evidence that anyone had actually acted on the incorrect advice provided by the AVN. The court did not make a judgement about the validity of the complaints, nor the information contained within them.<ref name=SupCourt/>\n\n====Changes to HCCC Act and new investigation====\n\nThe ruling resulted in a change in the law, allowing HCCC to initiate proceedings based on likelihood of harm, rather than having to wait for actual injury.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northernstar.com.au/news/laws-which-give-avn-power-silence-lobby-may-save-l/1862536/|title=Laws which give AVN power to silence lobby may save lives|last=Grewal|first=Jessica|date=10 May 2013|work=Northern Star|access-date=28 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> Following the passage of the Health Legislation Amendment Bill 2013<ref name=LegislationAmendment>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/nswbills.nsf/d6079cf53295ca7dca256e66001e39d2/0b02a796634005caca257b2c00138133?OpenDocument |title=Health Legislation Amendment Bill 2013 |work=NSW Parliament, Legislative Assembly |date=14 May 2013 |author=. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129171047/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/nswbills.nsf/d6079cf53295ca7dca256e66001e39d2/0b02a796634005caca257b2c00138133?OpenDocument |archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref> by the [[Parliament of New South Wales]], giving the HCCC powers to initiate investigations, and explore medical advice provided more generally than under the previous act, the NSW Premier [[Barry O'Farrell]] announced<ref name= newInvestigation>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/barryofarrell/status/339608475116109825 |author=O'Farrell, Barry |title=Announcement of New HCCC Investigation |work=NSW Premier via Twitter |date=28 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129171047/https://twitter.com/barryofarrell/status/339608475116109825 |archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref> that the Health Minister has advised [[Parliament|NSW Parliament]] the Health Care Complaints Commission is launching an investigation into the Australian Vaccination Network.\n\nThe HCCC concluded a second investigation into AVN in 2014 and published a new warning statement.<ref name=hccc2014/> The second public warning went further by scientifically addressing specific medical misinformation disseminated by AVN and concluded:\n:\"The Commission has established that AVN does not provide reliable information in relation to certain vaccines and vaccination more generally... AVN\u2019s dissemination of misleading, misrepresented and incorrect information about vaccination engenders fear and alarm and is likely to detrimentally affect the clinical management or care of its readers... the Commission urges general caution is exercised when using AVN\u2019s website or Facebook page to research vaccination and to consult other reliable sources, including speaking to a medical practitioner, to make an informed decision\".<ref name=hccc2014>{{Cite press release|title=Public statement- warning about the Australian Vaccination-skeptics Network, Inc. ('AVN'), formerly known as Australian Vaccination Network Inc. |work=NSW Health Care Complaints Commission |date=30 April 2014 |url=http://www.hccc.nsw.gov.au/Hearings---decisions/Public-statements-and-warnings/Public-statement---warning-about-the-Australian-Vaccination-skeptics-Network--Inc---AVN----formerly-known-as-Australian-Vaccination-Network-Inc- |author=. |accessdate=16 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310164854/http://www.hccc.nsw.gov.au/Hearings---decisions/Public-statements-and-warnings/Public-statement---warning-about-the-Australian-Vaccination-skeptics-Network--Inc---AVN----formerly-known-as-Australian-Vaccination-Network-Inc- |archivedate=10 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===NSW Office of Liquor, Gaming and Racing (OLGR) investigation===\n\nFollowing complaints that the AVN had been illegally fundraising without authority between 2 July 2007 and 2 June 2009, and a previous warning relating to the AVN being in breach of its fundraising authority conditions (as it did not have a \"mechanism to properly and effectively deal with complaints relating to fundraising\"), the NSW Office of Liquor, Gaming and Racing (OLGR) announced in February 2010 that they would conduct a full audit of the groups fundraising activities.<ref name=olgr>{{cite news |title=Vaccination Network to be Audited |author=Mcmillan, Mel |date=11 February 2010 |work=[[Northern Star (Australian newspaper)|The Northern Star]] |url=http://www.northernstar.com.au/story/2010/02/11/anti-immunisers-needled/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100213015910/http://www.northernstar.com.au/story/2010/02/11/anti-immunisers-needled/ |archivedate=13 February 2010 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n====OLGR Ruling====\n\nOn 4 August 2010, the OLGR announced that their audit of the AVN had \"detected a number of breaches of charity fund-raising laws\", including:\n* Fundraising without authority;\n* Unauthorised expenditure;\n* Failure to keep proper records of income and expenditure;\n* Possible breaches of the ''Charitable Trust Act, 1993'',<ref>{{cite web |title=NSW Charitable Trust Act, 1993|date=1993 |work=AUSTLII |url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/nsw/consol_act/cta1993201/}}</ref> which would be referred to the Department of Justice and the Attorney General.\n\nThe AVN was given 28 days to respond to the findings. President Meryl Dorey declined to comment on the issue.<ref name=OLGRlateline>{{Cite episode |title=AVN asked to defend charity status |url=http://mpegmedia.abc.net.au/lateline/video/podcast/r613432_4069585.m4v |series=Lateline \n|credits=Stewart, John \n|network=ABC TV \n|station=ABC1 \n|location=National \n|airdate=4 August 2010 \n|transcript=AVN asked to defend charity status \n|transcripturl=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2010/s2973753.htm}}</ref>\n\n=====Revocation of authority to fundraise=====\n[[Image:NSW Gov Gazette Week No.41, 2010, p 5253.png|thumb|right|Public notice. Revocation of A.V.N. Inc's authority to fundraise under Charitable Fundraising Act. NSW State Gazette No.41, 2010, p 5253.]]\nOn 14 October 2010, the Hon. Kevin Greene, M.P. revoked the AVN's authority to fundraise, meaning they are no longer permitted to conduct appeals or receive donations from members of the public.<ref name=\"olgr-abc\"/><ref name=\"olgr-gazette\"/> Reasons for the revocation were given as breaches of sections 31 (1) a, b and f of the ''Charitable Fundraising Act 1991'':\n* Their fundraising appeals have not been conducted in good faith for charitable purposes;\n* Their fundraising appeals have been improperly administered;\n* Their fundraising activities are not in the public interest.\n\nIn response to the revocation, the AVN issued a media release criticising the OLGR's decision as being politically motivated, and difficult to understand given that the \"revocation was based entirely upon the questionable decision by the HCCC\", rather than upon \"the simple errors\" detected by the OLGR during their audit of the organisation. Dorey appealed for the public to make donations to the AVN before the revocation took effect on 20 October 2010.<ref name=\"olgr-avn\">{{Cite press release |title=The Office of Liquor, Gaming and Racing revokes the AVN's charitable authority |work=Australian Vaccination Network |author=Dorey, Meryl |date=14 October 2010 |url=http://myemail.constantcontact.com/Media-Release---The-OLGR-s-political-decision.html?soid=1101800214009&aid=3DZE_VCpPSY |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120312021229/http://myemail.constantcontact.com/Media-Release---The-OLGR-s-political-decision.html?soid=1101800214009&aid=3DZE_VCpPSY |archivedate=12 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n=====Supreme Court appeal=====\nAs part of their appeal to the NSW Supreme Court in relation to the HCCC complaint, the AVN asked the court to invalidate the OLGR's revocation of their fundraising authority, asking them to grant [[certiorari]]. In February 2012, the Court rejected AVN's argument, dismissed this particular complaint, and the fundraising prohibition remained.<ref name=SupCourt/>\n\n=== NSW Office of Fair Trading name change order ===\n\nIn December 2012, the New South Wales Office of Fair Trading issued an order for the AVN to change its name within two months or be de-registered. The letter of action was delivered to the home of the organization's president, Meryl Dorey. It described the name as misleading and a detriment to the community. The Fair Trading Minister, Anthony Roberts, said that issue of vaccination was one of life and death and that the organization's activities endangered people's safety. Mr Roberts has warned other states against the AVN trying to register. Robert Vellar, the NSW Fair Trading Assistant Commissioner for Compliance and Enforcement, says the AVN's name has misled parents seeking information. Mr Vellar added that the NSW government intended to change definitions in the Associations Act to prevent groups from using names that were in conflict with their charter. The president of the AMA (NSW), Assoc Prof Brian Owler, said the AVN needed to take responsibility for information it gave to parents.<ref name=\"antivax2_ref\"/> The AVN is fighting the renaming order in the courts.<ref name=\"abc2013-06-13\">{{cite news|last=Harvey|first=Eliza|title=Australian Vaccination Network fights court order to change name|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-06-13/anti-vaccination-campaigners-trying-to-overturn-nsw-name-change/4752844|accessdate=20 June 2013|work=[[PM (ABC Radio)]]|date=13 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis order was challenged by the group. The challenge was dismissed, and on 25 November 2013 the New South Wales Office of Fair Trading order was upheld by the Administrative Decisions Tribunal.<ref name=\"FairTradingNSW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fairtrading.nsw.gov.au/ftw/About_us/News_and_events/Media_releases/2013_media_releases/20131125_australian_vaccination_network.page|title=Australian Vaccination Network ordered to change its name|date=25 November 2013|work=Office of Fair Trading NSW|author=.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401062528/http://www.fairtrading.nsw.gov.au/ftw/About_us/News_and_events/Media_releases/2013_media_releases/20131125_australian_vaccination_network.page|archivedate=1 April 2014}}</ref> In February 2014 the group changed its name to the Australian Vaccination-Skeptics Network.<ref name=\"abc-sceptical\"/>\n\n=== Comparison of vaccination to rape ===\nIn April 2015 the AVsN Facebook page drew international attention for publishing a simulated rape photo ad with text saying that vaccinations are \"forced penetration\"<ref name=smhrape>{{Cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/australian-vaccination-skeptics-network-compares-vaccines-to-rape-20150422-1mr0wk.html |title=Australian Vaccination Skeptics Network compares vaccines to rape |author=Schetzer, Alana |date=22 April 2015 |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |access-date=7 March 2016}}</ref> and asking \"do you really 'need' control over your own body?\"<ref name=indrape>{{Cite news |author=Campbell, Jamie |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/anti-vaccination-group-defends-advert-comparing-immunising-children-to-rape-10199080.html |title=Anti-vaccination group defends advert comparing immunising children to rape |date=24 April 2015 |work=[[The Independent]] (UK) |access-date=7 March 2016}}</ref> It drew criticism from the CEO of Domestic Violence Victoria, the Federal shadow Minister for Health [[Catherine King (politician)|Catherine King MP]],<ref name=smhrape/> the Federal Minister for Health [[Sussan Ley]] MP, the president of the [[Australian Medical Association|AMA]], the NSW Rape Crisis Centre, as well as supporters of the group.<ref name=newsrape>{{Cite news |url=http://www.news.com.au/national/australian-vaccination-skeptics-network-compares-vaccines-to-rape-in-facebook-post/news-story/adf91402c9d6d0268bedde998fded961 |title=Outrage as vaccines compared to rape |author=Dunlevy, Sue |date=22 April 2015 |work=[[News Limited]] |access-date=7 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nCatherine King MP said that \"equating doctors with rapists shows how completely unhinged the AVsN has become\".<ref name=indrape/> AVsN responded: \"This post isn't tasteless - it is honest. What truly IS tasteless is our elected government trying to tell us that we have to vaccinate our children even if we don't believe it is best for their health\".<ref name=smhrape/> President of the AVsN, Tasha David, claimed her organisation did not own or control the page.<ref name=newsrape/> Within days the Facebook group was reported as having been shut down.<ref name=indrape/> It was not the first time AVN had allegedly used vaccination-rape comparison,<ref name=nbrape>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ora.tv/offthegrid/article/2015/4/23/anti-vaccination-group-pulls-controversial-facebook-ad-comparing-vaccines-rape |title=Anti-Vaccination Group Pulls Controversial Facebook Ad Comparing Vaccines to Rape |author=Ventura, Jesse |date=23 April 2015 |work=NewsBreaker [[Ora TV]] |format=mp4 video |access-date=26 May 2016}}</ref> in 2011 it tweeted \"court orders rape of a child\" in relation to a court ordering a five-year-old girl to be vaccinated.<ref name=smhrape/>\n\n=== Other controversies ===\n\nIn March 2007, the AVN made certain erroneous comments on their website, including claims that the [[Australian Medical Association]](AMA) received funding from pharmaceutical companies and actively censored information provided to its members. These claims were factually incorrect, and the AMA took legal action against the AVN. The AVN withdrew the claims and issued a public apology on 21 March 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandatory Vaccination |author=Dorey, Meryl |date=21 March 2007 |url=http://avn.org.au/library/index.php/taking-action/mandatory-vaccination.html |work=AVN |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720234646/http://avn.org.au/library/index.php/taking-action/mandatory-vaccination.html |archivedate=20 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the Australian Vaccination Network's advice against vaccination, and their refusal to display the HCCC safety warning on their website, was included in ''Australian Doctor'' magazine's ''Top 50 Medical Scandals of the past 50 years''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Parnell |first=Kerri |title=Top 50 Medical Scandals |journal=Australian Doctor |volume=Top 50 supplement, 7th Edition |year=2011 |url=http://www.australiandoctor.com.au/top50/IMMUNISATION_STAND-OFF.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001212713/http://www.australiandoctor.com.au/top50/IMMUNISATION_STAND-OFF.asp |archivedate=1 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:ASI Bent Spoon Award.JPG|thumb|right|2009 winners: Meryl Dorey & The Australian (anti)Vaccination Network]]\nThe [[Australian Skeptics]] awarded their [[Bent Spoon Award]], \"presented annually to the perpetrator of the most preposterous piece of [[paranormal]] or [[pseudoscientific]] piffle\", to Meryl Dorey and the AVN in 2009, stating that the award had been earned through their \"scaremongering and misinformation about childhood vaccination\". In response, Dorey stated that winning the award meant she was \"on the right track\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=McMillan |first=Mel |title=Skeptics hand out Bent Spoon |newspaper=[[Northern Star (Australian newspaper)|The Northern Star]] |date=1 December 2009 |url=http://www.northernstar.com.au/story/2009/12/01/anti-vaccine-network-gets-dubious-award/ |accessdate=30 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, the AVN was accused of numerous copyright breaches relating to their sale of information packs containing photocopies of selected parts of old medical journal articles, newspaper reports and cartoons. After receiving complaints from authors and copyright holders, the AVN withdrew the packs from sale on their website. Several authors stated that they had not given permission for the AVN to reproduce the material and would seek payment for their past use. They also criticised the AVN's use of the articles as they were \"old and not based on current information\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Benson |first=Kate |title=Copyright breaches land group in trouble |newspaper=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |location=Sydney |publisher=Fairfax |date=1 September 2010 |url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/copyright-breaches-land-group-in-trouble-20100831-14fna.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903143041/http://www.smh.com.au/national/copyright-breaches-land-group-in-trouble-20100831-14fna.html |archivedate=3 September 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Political criticisms===\n\n====Federal Parliament====\nFollowing the AVN's public objections to the Australian Government's 1998 [[Australian Measles Control Campaign]], the then Federal Health Minister Michael Wooldridge issued a media release which was highly critical of the group, writing:\n:\"I am deeply concerned that media organisations risk giving credibility to the crackpot views of the AVN by publishing, without question, their untrue and deceitful claims. Ultimately, young children who are particularly vulnerable to measles could suffer if their parents were influenced by the anti-science, irrational views of the AVN.\"<ref name=\"wooldridge\"/>\n\nIn 2013, [[Australian Greens|Greens]] Senator [[Richard Di Natale]] put forward a motion calling for the Australian Vaccination Network to be disbanded, citing the risks that low-levels of vaccination posed to the health of children in Australia. The motion was passed by the [[Australian Senate]].<ref name=StopMotion>{{Cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-06-25/senate-passes-motion-urging-aust-vaccination-network-to-disband/4779882 |title=Senate motion calls on anti-vaccine group to disband |date=25 June 2013 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |author=. |access-date=2 March 2016}}</ref> Senator Di Natale condemned the organisation,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/comment/does-antivaccination-lobby-have-tacit-support-of-greens-20150413-1mju22.html |title=Does anti-vaccination lobby have tacit support of Greens? |last=Reith |first=Peter |date=14 April 2015 |newspaper=[[The Age]] |access-date=3 March 2016}}</ref> stating in a press release:\n:\"The AVN have gone so far as to promote measles as a healthy gift from mother nature and not the deadly disease it really is. As a doctor, I saw first-hand the tragedy these easily preventable diseases can cause.\n:Today the Senate has joined with the public health community to send a clear and strong message to those who are peddling lies about vaccines \u2013 they should pack up and go home.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://richard-di-natale.greensmps.org.au/content/media-releases/senate-anti-vax-group-pack-and-go-home |title=Senate to anti-vax group: Pack up and go home |author1=Di Natale |author2=Senator Richard |date=25 June 2013 |website=[[Australian Greens]] - media release |access-date=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n====NSW Parliament====\nIn a response to a parliamentary question about the AVN's statements regarding the [[MMR vaccine]], in September 2012 the NSW Minister for Health and Minister for Medical Research said:\n: \"The Australian Vaccination Network has not provided accurate information to parents about the risks and benefits of immunisation. Any link between the measles vaccine and autism has been conclusively discredited by numerous studies and reviews by credible experts, including the World Health Organization, the American Academy of Paediatrics and the UK Medical Research Council.\"<ref>{{Citation |last=Skinner |first=Jillian | title=2658\u2014Australian Vaccination Network |work=NSW Parliament Questions & Answers Paper |issue=119 |date=26 September 2012 |url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/la/qala.nsf/c1e52c2011c46013ca2574a20081ab75/9b7c1825497e4683ca257a610082b73e?OpenDocument |archive-date=20 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620020626/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/la/qala.nsf/c1e52c2011c46013ca2574a20081ab75/9b7c1825497e4683ca257a610082b73e?OpenDocument}}</ref>\n\nDuring the NSW parliamentary debate on the Health Legislation Amendment Bill 2013, the NSW shadow Health minister Andrew McDonald warned that the AVN's name and website were \"designed to mislead unsuspecting community members to believe that a balanced view about immunisation is being presented\" and that \"When provoked, Australian Vaccination Network's fellow travellers can and do behave reprehensibly,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hanstrans.nsf/V3ByKey/LA20130326/$File/LA20130326.pdf |title=Legislative Assembly, Hansard transcript |work=NSW Parliament |date=26 March 2013 |author=. |archivedate=8 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208223425/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hanstrans.nsf/V3ByKey/LA20130326/%24File/LA20130326.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref> while Mr Matt Kean MP described the AVN as \"a group of flat-earthers and wing-nuts who believe that vaccination is unnecessary. Indeed, the group has claimed that vaccination is harmful to individuals, which is contrary to all the scientific evidence.\" In further debate, members of parliament described the AVN as \"placing children at risk\", \"negligent\", \"misleading\" and \"disreputable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hanstrans.nsf/V3ByKey/LA20130430/$File/LA20130430.pdf |title=Legislative Assembly, Hansard transcript |work=NSW Parliament |date=30 April 2013 |author=. |archivedate=6 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206051017/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hanstrans.nsf/V3ByKey/LA20130430/%24File/LA20130430.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe late NSW Greens [[John Kaye (politician)|MLC John Kaye]] lobbied against, what he called, AVN's \"voodoo claims and conspiracy theories\". Describing AVN as \"disgraceful\", he said: \"Spreading misinformation about childhood immunisation could be deadly\".<ref name=\"echo-byron\">{{cite news |url=http://www.echo.net.au/2013/04/greens-attack-voodoo-vaccination-opponents/ |title=Greens attack 'voodoo' vaccination opponents |author=Dobney, Chris |date=12 April 2013 |work=The [[Byron Shire Echo]] |page=9 |accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the NSW Legislative Council, the Hon. Peter Phelps described the AVN as \"insane\", while the Hon. Trevor Khan called the AVN a \"danger to public health\" for \"touting unscientific propaganda\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hanstrans.nsf/V3ByKey/LC20130508/$File/LC20130508.pdf |title=Legislative Assembly, Hansard transcript |work=NSW Parliament |date=8 May 2013 |author=. |archivedate=6 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206044003/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hanstrans.nsf/V3ByKey/LC20130508/%24File/LC20130508.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Hon. Anthony John Roberts, NSW Minister for Fair Trading said that \"It is incredibly irresponsible for an avowedly anti-vaccination group to advertise itself as a balanced source of information on vaccination. Such action is not only misleading to the public but also dangerous to those who believe they are referring to evidence-based medical advice...\" The Government, the medical community and the Australian Medical Association led by Associate Professor Brian Owler are in agreement that the name Australian Vaccination Network \"is unacceptable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hanstrans.nsf/V3ByKey/LA20130509/$File/LA20130509.pdf |title=Legislative Assembly, Hansard transcript |work=NSW Parliament |date=9 May 2013 |author=. |archivedate=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054805/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hanstrans.nsf/V3ByKey/LA20130509/%24File/LA20130509.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Queensland Parliament====\nIn December 2011 the Queensland Minister for Health, Geoff Wilson, issued a media statement criticising the AVN with the following comment, \"For the small number of people who might be entertained by what Ms Dorey has to say, Woodford Folk Festival has a place for everyone. Just don't take her nonsense too seriously.\" The Hon. Geoff Wilson also added, \"The fact is vaccinations have saved millions of lives. Their invention was a miracle of scientific achievement.\" <ref>{{Citation |last=Wilson M.P. |first=Geoff |title=Statement from the Minister for Health and the Chief Health Officer | work=Queensland Government |issue=78177 |date=15 December 2011| url=http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/Id/78177}}</ref>\n\n===Other criticisms===\n\nIn 2002 while speaking about low vaccination rates in the NSW Northern Rivers region, the Hon. [[Brian Pezzutti]] criticised Meryl Dorey in the NSW Legislative Council:\n:\"only 60 per cent of children in the Byron Bay area in the 12 to 15 month age group\u2014the very young and most vulnerable\u2014 are immunised. That is mainly because of the activities of a woman called Meryl Dorey, who lives in Byron Bay and who has decided not to immunise her children and who regularly claims that immunisation is not necessary. She campaigns against immunisation.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Pezzutti |first=Brian |title=Immunisation |journal=Hansard of the NSW Legislative Council |page=4402 |date=3 September 2002 |url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LC20020903039 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022200853/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LC20020903039 |archive-date=22 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAustralian entrepreneur [[Dick Smith (entrepreneur)|Dick Smith]], who had previously run a national ad in ''[[The Australian]]'' asking parents to ignore AVN's claims, has been highly critical of the organisation, stating:\n: \"They are actually anti-vaccination, and they should put on every bit of their material that they are anti-vaccination in great big words. They have every right for that belief but they should communicate it clearly so people are not misled.\" and\n: \"I think they're choosing not to vaccinate because they don't understand risk management - they are told that there is a risk with vaccination - now everything in life has a risk. There's a minute risk but it's been proved all over the world that the advantages far outweigh the risk.\"<ref name=\"smith\"/><ref name=\"Tim Brunero\"/>\n\nFollowing the AVN's decision to hold an anti-vaccination seminar at the Western Australian State Library, the Shadow Arts Minister John Hyde criticised the state Government for allowing the group to \"push its anti-vaccine message\", saying:\n: \"Why should a group that endangers the lives of WA children be allowed to speak and promote their cause at a taxpayer-funded venue dedicated to learning? Their dangerous propaganda which is putting children at risk of polio, smallpox, cholera and other preventable diseases should not be able to gain respectability by using the good name of the State Library.\"<ref name=Perth/>\n\nDuring an interview on ABC Lateline in July 2010, the 1997 [[Australian of the Year]] and 1996 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize for Medicine]] laureate, immunologist [[Peter C. Doherty]] described the AVN's attempts to reduce the child immunisation rate as a \"Crime against Humanity\".<ref name=HCCClateline/>\n\nIn a 2016 press release responding to questions from AVsN's Meryl Dorey, the [[Australian Sex Party]] publicly stated:<ref name=aspvaxbi>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessinsider.com.au/the-australian-sex-party-wrote-this-devastating-response-to-an-anti-vaccination-campaigner-looking-for-support-2016-5 |title=The Australian Sex Party wrote this devastating response to an anti-vaccination campaigner looking for support |author=Kimmorley, Sarah |date=16 May 2016 |work=Business Insider |accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n:\"The safety and efficacy of vaccination is not an area of scientific controversy. The claim that governments and scientists are all conspiring to mislead us ... is absurd and irresponsible... The claims of the anti-vaccination movement have been thoroughly debunked. Choosing not to vaccinate your children amounts to medical neglect; this is a serious ethical issue... We at the Australian Sex Party would like to encourage parents who are questioning what\u2019s right for their children, to follow the advice of the scientific and medical communities, rather than charlatans and conspiracy theorists\".<ref name=aspvaxpr>{{cite press release |url=http://www.sexparty.org.au/news-article/215-asxp-responds-to-vaccination-skeptics |title=ASXP responds to vaccination skeptics |author=Austin, Darren |date=May 2016 |work=[[Australian Sex Party]] |accessdate=16 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515135023/http://www.sexparty.org.au/news-article/215-asxp-responds-to-vaccination-skeptics |archive-date=15 May 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Stop the Australian Vaccination Network group===\n\nIn May 2009, immediately after the filming of the second ''Sunday Night'' television program covering the Pertussis death of Dana McCaffery, the ''Stop the AVN'' group was formed by Daniel Raffaele to \"challenge the Australian Vaccination Network (AVN)\".<ref name=savn/><ref name=\"savn-award\">{{Cite news |title=Fighting For Reason |author=. |newspaper=The Bay Post |location=Bateman's Bay NSW |page=46 |date=15 December 2010}}</ref> Members of the group began investigating the information provided by the AVN, and submitted complaints to the HCCC and OLGR.<ref name=\"SMH\"/><ref name=olgr/> The AVN's Meryl Dorey accused the group of \"attacking the AVN unfairly\".\n\nIn November 2010, the [[Australian Skeptics]] collectively presented the 2700 members of the SAVN group with the ''Skeptic of the Year'' award, and SAVN members Ken McLeod and Wendy Wilkinson with the ''Thornett Award For the Promotion Of Reason''.<ref name=\"savn-award\"/>\n\n===American Airlines cancels an AVN advertisement===\nIn April 2012, [[American Airlines]] pulled an AVN ad that was scheduled to appear on American Airlines' in-flight TV channel. Dorey stated that \"We were offered a three minute slot, but because of the controversy from 'Stop the AVN' we lost it.\"<ref name=aa_pulls_ad>{{Cite news |last=Burton-Bradley |first=Robert |title=Australian Vaccination Network's ad pulled by American Airlines after 'backlash' |work=[[Herald Sun]] |location=Melbourne |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |date=26 April 2012 |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/more-news/australian-vaccination-networks-ad-pulled-by-american-airlines-after-backlash/story-e6frf7l6-1226338838579 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513183854/http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/australian-vaccination-networks-ad-pulled-by-american-airlines-after-backlash/story-e6frfq80-1226338838579 |archivedate=13 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nFounder of the 'Stop the AVN' group, Daniel Raffaele, who initiated the campaign to stop the ad commented, \"Basically when it comes to information the AVN provides misinformation.\"<ref name=aa_pulls_ad />\n\n===Therapeutic Goods Administration complaint===\n\nThe AVN has been the subject of a complaint over the advertising of [[Cansema|black salve]], and the complaint was found to be justified by the [[Therapeutic Goods Administration]]'s Complaints Resolution Panel.<ref name=\"TGA CRP finding against AVN\">{{Cite web |title=Complaint against AVN over black salve advertising |work=(Australian) [[Therapeutic Goods Administration]] Complaints Resolution Panel |date=16 August 2012 |url=http://www.tgacrp.com.au/index.cfm?pageID=13&special=complaint_single&complaintID=2081 |author=. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513090950/https://www.docdroid.net/hCtfiFN/tgacrp-com-au.rtf.html |archivedate=13 May 2016 }}</ref> The Panel's determination was issued on 3 December 2012.<ref name=\"TGA decision against AVN\">{{Cite web |title=Decision under regulation 9 of the Therapeutic Goods Regulations 1990 in relation to an advertisement about the product 'black salve' |date=16 May 2013 |url=http://www.tga.gov.au/industry/advertising-reg9-2012-04-022-black-salve.htm |accessdate=19 May 2013 |work=(Australian) [[Therapeutic Goods Administration]] |author=.}}</ref> On 16 May 2013, the delegate of the Secretary to the [[Department of Health and Ageing]] decided to order the AVN to carry out actions as the AVN had not fully complied with the Panel's determination.\n\nDorey and Leon Pittard (of Fair Dinkum Radio) have been the subject of an additional complaint, which was also found to be justified.<ref name=\"TGA CRP finding against Meryl Dorey and Leon Pittard\">{{Cite web |title=Complaint against Meryl Dorey and Leon Pittard over black salve advertising |work=(Australian) [[Therapeutic Goods Administration]] Complaints Resolution Panel |date=16 August 2012 |url=http://www.tgacrp.com.au/index.cfm?pageID=13&special=complaint_single&complaintID=2114 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514065345/https://www.docdroid.net/bDAXUg2/tgacrp-com-au-2.rtf.html |archivedate=14 May 2016 |author=. }}</ref> Dorey has presented a [[Freeman on the land]] defence in relation to that complaint.<ref name=\"MD Freeman of the Land defence\">{{Cite web |author='Meryl Dorey's personal representative' |title=Offer to Settle in Private |work=TGA FOI release |date=16 July 2012 |url=https://www.tga.gov.au/sites/default/files/foi-181-1213-12.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516220615/https://www.tga.gov.au/sites/default/files/foi-181-1213-12.pdf |archivedate=16 May 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.avn.org.au/ Official website]\n* [http://www.stopavn.com/ Stop The AVN]\n\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination organizations]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian health activists]]\n", "name_user": "194.193.174.11", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australian_Vaccination-risks_Network"}
